// Per-row Review checkpoints for the roadmap (window.REVIEWS["<branchId>:<tierIndex>"]).
window.REVIEWS = {"antidepressants:0":[{"id":"rev_antidepressants_0_1","stem":"A patient stopped his SSRI abruptly 2 days ago and now has dizziness, electric-shock 'brain zap' sensations, nausea and flu-like malaise. Which SSRI is most likely responsible for this severe discontinuation syndrome?","options":["Sertraline","Fluoxetine","Paroxetine","Escitalopram"],"answer":"Paroxetine","explanation":"Paroxetine has the worst discontinuation syndrome of the SSRIs — a short half-life (~21 h) with no active metabolite plus anticholinergic rebound. Fluoxetine is the opposite extreme: its long-acting metabolite norfluoxetine (7–15 days) self-tapers, so discontinuation is rare. Sertraline and escitalopram are intermediate.","meds":["sertraline","fluoxetine","paroxetine","escitalopram"],"focus":"discontinuation syndrome","source":{"name":"Paroxetine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"paroxetine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_0_2","stem":"Which SSRI carries a dose-dependent QT-prolongation risk that led to a hard maximum of 40 mg/day (20 mg/day in the elderly, hepatic impairment, or CYP2C19 poor metabolizers)?","options":["Citalopram","Sertraline","Escitalopram","Fluoxetine"],"answer":"Citalopram","explanation":"Citalopram is the QT SSRI, with regulator-mandated dose ceilings for dose-dependent QTc prolongation. Its purified S-enantiomer escitalopram prolongs QT far less and has no comparable hard cap. Sertraline and fluoxetine are not notable QT offenders.","meds":["citalopram","sertraline","escitalopram","fluoxetine"],"focus":"QT prolongation / dose ceiling","source":{"name":"Citalopram label (QT warning)","origin":"openfda"},"answerId":"citalopram"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_0_3","stem":"You want to start an SSRI in a young adult with anergic, hypersomnic depression who is frequently non-adherent and often misses doses. Which agent is the most activating and has the longest half-life, so missed doses are least problematic and discontinuation is minimal?","options":["Paroxetine","Fluoxetine","Sertraline","Citalopram"],"answer":"Fluoxetine","explanation":"Fluoxetine is the most activating SSRI (dose in the morning; can worsen initial anxiety/insomnia) and has the longest half-life via norfluoxetine (7–15 days), so it tolerates missed doses and rarely causes discontinuation symptoms. Paroxetine is sedating with the worst discontinuation; sertraline and citalopram are intermediate.","meds":["paroxetine","fluoxetine","sertraline","citalopram"],"focus":"half-life / activation","source":{"name":"Fluoxetine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"fluoxetine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_0_4","stem":"A patient three weeks post-myocardial infarction develops major depression. Which SSRI has the best cardiac-safety evidence (SADHART) and characteristically causes diarrhea as its signature GI effect?","options":["Paroxetine","Fluoxetine","Citalopram","Sertraline"],"answer":"Sertraline","explanation":"Sertraline is the cardiac-preferred SSRI (SADHART) with a clean interaction profile and diarrhea as its hallmark GI effect. Citalopram would be a QT concern in cardiac patients; paroxetine is anticholinergic and sedating; fluoxetine is activating and a potent CYP2D6 inhibitor.","meds":["paroxetine","fluoxetine","citalopram","sertraline"],"focus":"cardiac safety / GI signature","source":{"name":"SADHART / CANMAT","origin":"canmat"},"answerId":"sertraline"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_0_5","stem":"Which SSRI is the purified active S-enantiomer of another SSRI in this group, is frequently chosen first-line for its tolerability and clean interaction profile, and carries a generalized anxiety disorder indication?","options":["Escitalopram","Citalopram","Fluoxetine","Paroxetine"],"answer":"Escitalopram","explanation":"Escitalopram is the S-enantiomer of citalopram (~20 mg escitalopram ≈ 40 mg citalopram) but with a better tolerability/interaction profile, far less QT effect, and a GAD indication. Fluoxetine (activating, potent 2D6 inhibitor) and paroxetine (anticholinergic, worst discontinuation) are less clean.","meds":["escitalopram","citalopram","fluoxetine","paroxetine"],"focus":"enantiomer relationship / tolerability","source":{"name":"CANMAT MDD guidelines","origin":"canmat"},"answerId":"escitalopram"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_0_6","stem":"A woman on tamoxifen for breast cancer needs an SSRI for depression. Which agent should be AVOIDED because its potent CYP2D6 inhibition blocks conversion of tamoxifen to its active metabolite endoxifen?","options":["Sertraline","Paroxetine","Escitalopram","Citalopram"],"answer":"Paroxetine","explanation":"Paroxetine is a potent CYP2D6 inhibitor and the classic SSRI to avoid with tamoxifen — it lowers active endoxifen and has been linked to worse breast-cancer outcomes. Sertraline, escitalopram and citalopram are weak 2D6 inhibitors and are preferred here. (Fluoxetine is also a potent 2D6 inhibitor and would likewise be avoided.)","meds":["sertraline","paroxetine","escitalopram","citalopram"],"focus":"CYP2D6 inhibition (tamoxifen)","source":{"name":"Paroxetine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"paroxetine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_0_7","stem":"A breastfeeding mother with postpartum depression needs an SSRI. Which agent has the most reassuring lactation data and is generally preferred in pregnancy, whereas one of the other options carries a first-trimester cardiac-malformation signal?","options":["Paroxetine","Fluoxetine","Sertraline","Citalopram"],"answer":"Sertraline","explanation":"Sertraline has low breast-milk transfer and the best pregnancy/lactation evidence, making it a first choice peripartum. Paroxetine is the SSRI generally avoided in pregnancy because of a signal for fetal cardiac (septal) defects. Fluoxetine's very long half-life persists in the neonate; citalopram is a QT consideration.","meds":["paroxetine","fluoxetine","sertraline","citalopram"],"focus":"pregnancy / lactation safety","source":{"name":"CANMAT / sertraline monograph","origin":"canmat"},"answerId":"sertraline"}],"antidepressants:1":[{"id":"rev_antidepressants_1_1","stem":"A patient titrated above 150 mg/day of an SNRI develops a sustained rise in diastolic blood pressure. Which agent is most classically associated with this dose-dependent noradrenergic hypertension, warranting blood-pressure monitoring during titration?","options":["Venlafaxine","Duloxetine","Desvenlafaxine","Bupropion"],"answer":"Venlafaxine","explanation":"Venlafaxine's noradrenergic effect (and dose-dependent hypertension) emerges above ~150 mg/day — check BP as you push the dose. Desvenlafaxine (its active metabolite) also raises BP but has flat 50 mg dosing; duloxetine's BP effect is milder; bupropion is an NDRI that can raise BP but is not the prototype for dose-dependent SNRI hypertension.","meds":["venlafaxine","duloxetine","desvenlafaxine","bupropion"],"focus":"dose-dependent hypertension","source":{"name":"Venlafaxine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"venlafaxine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_1_2","stem":"A patient with major depression and comorbid diabetic peripheral neuropathy would benefit most from an antidepressant with a formal chronic-pain indication — but it must be avoided in significant liver disease or heavy alcohol use. Which agent?","options":["Venlafaxine","Duloxetine","Desvenlafaxine","Mirtazapine"],"answer":"Duloxetine","explanation":"Duloxetine has formal indications for diabetic neuropathy, fibromyalgia and chronic musculoskeletal pain (its analgesia is partly noradrenergic and can precede mood benefit), but it carries a hepatotoxicity caution and should be avoided in liver disease or substantial alcohol use. Venlafaxine and desvenlafaxine lack the same pain indications; mirtazapine is not an analgesic.","meds":["venlafaxine","duloxetine","desvenlafaxine","mirtazapine"],"focus":"chronic-pain indication / hepatotoxicity","source":{"name":"Duloxetine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"duloxetine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_1_3","stem":"A CYP2D6 poor metabolizer already taking several CYP-interacting drugs needs an SNRI with predictable levels and minimal CYP involvement. Which agent — itself the active metabolite of another SNRI — is cleared mainly by glucuronidation and essentially bypasses CYP2D6?","options":["Desvenlafaxine","Venlafaxine","Duloxetine","Fluvoxamine"],"answer":"Desvenlafaxine","explanation":"Desvenlafaxine IS O-desmethylvenlafaxine (venlafaxine's active metabolite); it is cleared largely by UGT glucuronidation with negligible CYP2D6 dependence, giving predictable levels and few interactions, plus flat 50 mg dosing. Venlafaxine is a CYP2D6 substrate; duloxetine involves CYP1A2/2D6; fluvoxamine is the most interaction-prone SSRI.","meds":["desvenlafaxine","venlafaxine","duloxetine","fluvoxamine"],"focus":"CYP2D6-independent metabolism","source":{"name":"Desvenlafaxine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"desvenlafaxine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_1_4","stem":"A patient responding to an SSRI is distressed by sexual dysfunction and modest weight gain. Which agent — free of serotonergic activity — is the best choice to switch to or add, given it typically causes no sexual dysfunction and is weight-neutral or causes weight loss?","options":["Mirtazapine","Venlafaxine","Duloxetine","Bupropion"],"answer":"Bupropion","explanation":"Bupropion is an NDRI with no serotonergic activity, so it neither causes sexual dysfunction (it is used to augment SSRI-induced sexual side effects) nor weight gain (often weight loss). Mirtazapine causes the most weight gain of this group; venlafaxine and duloxetine share SSRI-like sexual side effects.","meds":["mirtazapine","venlafaxine","duloxetine","bupropion"],"focus":"sexual dysfunction / weight neutrality","source":{"name":"Bupropion product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"bupropion"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_1_5","stem":"An underweight, cachectic patient with depression, severe insomnia and poor appetite would benefit most from which agent — one whose sedation and appetite stimulation are paradoxically STRONGER at LOW doses?","options":["Mirtazapine","Bupropion","Venlafaxine","Duloxetine"],"answer":"Mirtazapine","explanation":"Mirtazapine (a presynaptic α2 antagonist / NaSSA) is ideal for depression with insomnia and weight loss; its potent H1 antihistamine effect dominates at LOW doses (sedation and appetite are greater at 7.5–15 mg than at higher doses, where added noradrenergic drive offsets it), and 5-HT3 blockade gives an antiemetic effect. Bupropion would suppress appetite and worsen insomnia.","meds":["mirtazapine","bupropion","venlafaxine","duloxetine"],"focus":"sedation/appetite (low-dose H1 predominance)","source":{"name":"Mirtazapine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"mirtazapine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_1_6","stem":"A patient stabilized on clozapine is started on a new antidepressant and days later develops rising sedation, sialorrhea and a supratherapeutic clozapine level. Which agent — a potent CYP1A2 inhibitor — is the culprit?","options":["Fluvoxamine","Duloxetine","Bupropion","Mirtazapine"],"answer":"Fluvoxamine","explanation":"Fluvoxamine is the most interaction-prone SSRI: as a potent CYP1A2 (and 2C19) inhibitor it sharply raises clozapine, olanzapine, theophylline, caffeine and tizanidine levels. Duloxetine is a CYP1A2 SUBSTRATE (its own levels rise with fluvoxamine) but not a potent 1A2 inhibitor; bupropion and mirtazapine do not drive this interaction.","meds":["fluvoxamine","duloxetine","bupropion","mirtazapine"],"focus":"CYP1A2 inhibition (clozapine)","source":{"name":"Fluvoxamine label / DDI","origin":"openfda"},"answerId":"fluvoxamine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_1_7","stem":"Which antidepressant is contraindicated in a patient with active bulimia nervosa or a seizure disorder, and should be avoided during abrupt alcohol or benzodiazepine withdrawal, because it lowers the seizure threshold?","options":["Mirtazapine","Bupropion","Venlafaxine","Fluvoxamine"],"answer":"Bupropion","explanation":"Bupropion lowers the seizure threshold in a dose-dependent way and is contraindicated in seizure disorders and in bulimia/anorexia (higher seizure incidence, compounded by purging-related electrolyte shifts), and should be avoided with abrupt alcohol/benzodiazepine withdrawal. The other agents do not carry these specific contraindications.","meds":["mirtazapine","bupropion","venlafaxine","fluvoxamine"],"focus":"seizure threshold / eating-disorder contraindication","source":{"name":"Bupropion XL label (contraindications)","origin":"openfda"},"answerId":"bupropion"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_1_8","stem":"Among these agents, which has the worst discontinuation syndrome — driven by the shortest half-life — such that even a single missed dose can trigger dizziness, irritability and 'brain zaps'?","options":["Bupropion","Mirtazapine","Venlafaxine","Duloxetine"],"answer":"Venlafaxine","explanation":"Venlafaxine has the shortest half-life here (~5 h; active metabolite ~11 h), giving the most abrupt, severe discontinuation syndrome of the antidepressants — never stop it abruptly. Bupropion and mirtazapine have minimal serotonergic discontinuation; duloxetine is intermediate.","meds":["bupropion","mirtazapine","venlafaxine","duloxetine"],"focus":"discontinuation syndrome","source":{"name":"Venlafaxine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"venlafaxine"}],"antidepressants:2":[{"id":"rev_antidepressants_2_1","stem":"A man taking a sedating antidepressant (used mainly at low dose for sleep) presents with a painful erection lasting over 4 hours. Which agent's α1-adrenergic blockade is responsible for this urologic emergency?","options":["Vortioxetine","Trazodone","Levomilnacipran","Moclobemide"],"answer":"Trazodone","explanation":"Trazodone (a SARI) causes priapism via α1-adrenergic blockade — the classic board fact; warn men to seek emergency care for an erection lasting >4 h. Its α1/H1 effects also make it a low-dose hypnotic with orthostatic hypotension. Vortioxetine, levomilnacipran and moclobemide do not cause priapism.","meds":["vortioxetine","trazodone","levomilnacipran","moclobemide"],"focus":"priapism (α1 blockade)","source":{"name":"Trazodone product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"trazodone"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_2_2","stem":"A Canadian patient needs an MAO inhibitor but cannot reliably follow a strict low-tyramine diet. Which agent — a reversible inhibitor of MAO-A available in Canada but not the US — lets dietary tyramine competitively displace it, so no strict diet is required and washout is short?","options":["Vortioxetine","Trazodone","Levomilnacipran","Moclobemide"],"answer":"Moclobemide","explanation":"Moclobemide is a RIMA (reversible inhibitor of MAO-A): tyramine outcompetes it at the enzyme, so there is no strict diet and only a short washout (very short half-life). It is marketed in Canada (Manerix), not the US. The others are not MAOIs — though note that moclobemide's serotonin-syndrome contraindications still apply.","meds":["vortioxetine","trazodone","levomilnacipran","moclobemide"],"focus":"RIMA / tyramine handling","source":{"name":"Moclobemide (Manerix) monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"moclobemide"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_2_3","stem":"Which agent is a 'multimodal' antidepressant — combining serotonin reuptake inhibition with direct 5-HT receptor modulation (5-HT1A agonism, 5-HT3/5-HT7 antagonism) — marketed for possible pro-cognitive benefit and a lower rate of sexual dysfunction than classic SSRIs?","options":["Vortioxetine","Trazodone","Levomilnacipran","Moclobemide"],"answer":"Vortioxetine","explanation":"Vortioxetine combines SERT inhibition with direct 5-HT receptor modulation, is promoted for pro-cognitive effects (processing speed/executive function) and has lower sexual dysfunction than classic SSRIs; dose-dependent nausea is its main side effect. Trazodone is a sedating SARI; levomilnacipran an SNRI; moclobemide a RIMA.","meds":["vortioxetine","trazodone","levomilnacipran","moclobemide"],"focus":"multimodal mechanism / cognition","source":{"name":"Vortioxetine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"vortioxetine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_2_4","stem":"Which second-line agent is the most noradrenergic-predominant SNRI (greater potency at NET than SERT), so patients more often show tachycardia, blood-pressure rise and urinary hesitancy than with the usual serotonergic-leaning SNRIs?","options":["Vortioxetine","Moclobemide","Levomilnacipran","Trazodone"],"answer":"Levomilnacipran","explanation":"Levomilnacipran is the SNRI with NET > SERT potency (the reverse of most), so noradrenergic effects — tachycardia, hypertension, urinary hesitancy, sweating — predominate. It is a CYP3A4 substrate (cap the dose with strong 3A4 inhibitors and in renal impairment). The others are not noradrenergic-predominant SNRIs.","meds":["vortioxetine","moclobemide","levomilnacipran","trazodone"],"focus":"noradrenergic-predominant SNRI","source":{"name":"Levomilnacipran (Fetzima) label","origin":"openfda"},"answerId":"levomilnacipran"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_2_5","stem":"Despite being 'diet-liberal' and reversible, which of these still MUST NOT be combined with an SSRI, tramadol, meperidine or dextromethorphan because its risk of serotonin syndrome is unchanged from that of an irreversible MAOI?","options":["Vortioxetine","Trazodone","Moclobemide","Levomilnacipran"],"answer":"Moclobemide","explanation":"Moclobemide's reversibility lowers the TYRAMINE/hypertensive risk, but it is still an MAO-A inhibitor, so the SEROTONIN-syndrome contraindications (SSRIs/SNRIs, tramadol, meperidine, dextromethorphan, triptans) are unchanged — a common misconception that it is 'safe.' Trazodone, vortioxetine and levomilnacipran are serotonergic but are not MAOIs.","meds":["vortioxetine","trazodone","moclobemide","levomilnacipran"],"focus":"serotonin-syndrome risk persists (RIMA)","source":{"name":"Moclobemide (Manerix) monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"moclobemide"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_2_6","stem":"An older man with benign prostatic hyperplasia and borderline-controlled hypertension needs a second-line antidepressant. Which agent is least ideal because its strong noradrenergic action can worsen urinary hesitancy/retention and raise heart rate and blood pressure?","options":["Trazodone","Levomilnacipran","Vortioxetine","Moclobemide"],"answer":"Levomilnacipran","explanation":"Levomilnacipran's NET-predominant action commonly causes urinary hesitancy, tachycardia and blood-pressure elevation — problematic with BPH and hypertension. Vortioxetine and moclobemide lack these noradrenergic effects; trazodone's α1 blockade tends to relax bladder-neck tone but risks orthostatic hypotension instead.","meds":["trazodone","levomilnacipran","vortioxetine","moclobemide"],"focus":"urinary retention / noradrenergic caution","source":{"name":"Levomilnacipran (Fetzima) label","origin":"openfda"},"answerId":"levomilnacipran"}],"antidepressants:3":[{"id":"rev_antidepressants_3_1","stem":"A patient with severe OCD who has failed SSRIs is considered for a tricyclic. Which TCA is the most serotonergic and the historical gold-standard for OCD — yet also has the highest seizure risk, capping the dose near 250 mg/day?","options":["Amitriptyline","Nortriptyline","Clomipramine","Imipramine"],"answer":"Clomipramine","explanation":"Clomipramine is the most serotonergic TCA and the only one with robust OCD efficacy. That potent serotonergic action comes with the highest seizure risk of the TCAs (dose-dependent, hence the ~250 mg/day ceiling). Amitriptyline, nortriptyline and imipramine lack clomipramine's OCD efficacy.","meds":["amitriptyline","nortriptyline","clomipramine","imipramine"],"focus":"most serotonergic / OCD / seizure risk","source":{"name":"Clomipramine monograph / CANMAT","origin":"canmat"},"answerId":"clomipramine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_3_2","stem":"Which TCA is a secondary amine notable for a true therapeutic window (~50–150 ng/mL) — where levels ABOVE the window can reduce efficacy — making it a rare antidepressant guided by therapeutic drug monitoring, and the best-tolerated/least-orthostatic TCA, preferred in the elderly?","options":["Nortriptyline","Amitriptyline","Clomipramine","Desipramine"],"answer":"Nortriptyline","explanation":"Nortriptyline (a secondary amine, the active metabolite of amitriptyline) has a genuine therapeutic window with a curvilinear response, so both sub- and supra-therapeutic levels underperform — a classic TDM agent. It is the least orthostatic and best-tolerated TCA, favoured in the elderly. Amitriptyline and clomipramine are sedating tertiary amines; desipramine is activating.","meds":["nortriptyline","amitriptyline","clomipramine","desipramine"],"focus":"therapeutic window / TDM","source":{"name":"Nortriptyline product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"nortriptyline"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_3_3","stem":"Which TCA is the most noradrenergic-selective and least anticholinergic/sedating — effectively the closest to a 'clean,' activating tricyclic — but is a strong CYP2D6 substrate whose (cardiotoxic) levels rise sharply with fluoxetine, paroxetine or bupropion?","options":["Amitriptyline","Doxepin","Clomipramine","Desipramine"],"answer":"Desipramine","explanation":"Desipramine (secondary amine, the metabolite of imipramine) is the most selective noradrenergic reuptake inhibitor and least anticholinergic/sedating TCA, so it is activating. As a CYP2D6 substrate, its levels climb with potent 2D6 inhibitors — a concern given TCA cardiotoxicity. Amitriptyline, doxepin and clomipramine are sedating, anticholinergic tertiary amines.","meds":["amitriptyline","doxepin","clomipramine","desipramine"],"focus":"secondary-amine NE selectivity / activation","source":{"name":"Desipramine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"desipramine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_3_4","stem":"Which tricyclic is one of the most potent H1 antihistamines available and, at very low dose (3–6 mg), is repurposed as a selective histamine-blocking hypnotic for sleep maintenance — with minimal anticholinergic or cardiac toxicity at that dose?","options":["Doxepin","Amitriptyline","Nortriptyline","Trimipramine"],"answer":"Doxepin","explanation":"Doxepin is an exceptionally potent H1 antagonist; at 3–6 mg it acts as a near-pure antihistamine hypnotic with negligible TCA toxicity, whereas full antidepressant doses behave like any sedating tertiary amine (anticholinergic, cardiotoxic in overdose). Amitriptyline and trimipramine are also sedating but are not used as selective low-dose H1 hypnotics; nortriptyline is comparatively activating.","meds":["doxepin","amitriptyline","nortriptyline","trimipramine"],"focus":"low-dose H1 hypnotic","source":{"name":"Doxepin (low-dose) monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"doxepin"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_3_5","stem":"A patient on a 'tricyclic' develops akathisia, parkinsonism and hyperprolactinemia, and later tardive dyskinesia. Which agent — a metabolite of the antipsychotic loxapine — has D2 antagonism that explains these extrapyramidal effects (and a risk of neuroleptic malignant syndrome)?","options":["Maprotiline","Amoxapine","Nortriptyline","Desipramine"],"answer":"Amoxapine","explanation":"Amoxapine is the odd one out: as a metabolite of loxapine it blocks D2 receptors, so unlike other TCAs it can cause EPS, tardive dyskinesia, hyperprolactinemia and even NMS. Its overdose is also especially dangerous (severe seizures/status epilepticus and reports of acute renal failure). Maprotiline, nortriptyline and desipramine lack meaningful D2 blockade.","meds":["maprotiline","amoxapine","nortriptyline","desipramine"],"focus":"D2 antagonism → EPS/TD/NMS","source":{"name":"Amoxapine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"amoxapine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_3_6","stem":"Which prototype tertiary-amine TCA is classically used for childhood nocturnal enuresis and for panic disorder, and is demethylated to the secondary amine desipramine?","options":["Amitriptyline","Clomipramine","Imipramine","Nortriptyline"],"answer":"Imipramine","explanation":"Imipramine is the prototype TCA, with historical indications for childhood nocturnal enuresis and panic disorder; it is demethylated to desipramine (mirroring amitriptyline→nortriptyline). Its overdose lethality is a special concern when tablets are kept in homes with children. Amitriptyline, clomipramine and nortriptyline do not carry the enuresis indication.","meds":["amitriptyline","clomipramine","imipramine","nortriptyline"],"focus":"enuresis / panic indication","source":{"name":"Imipramine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"imipramine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_3_7","stem":"Which TCA is the most sedating and most anticholinergic, and at low dose is widely used off-label for migraine prophylaxis, neuropathic pain and insomnia — while, like all TCAs, remaining potentially lethal in overdose (wide QRS, arrhythmia)?","options":["Desipramine","Amitriptyline","Protriptyline","Nortriptyline"],"answer":"Amitriptyline","explanation":"Amitriptyline is the prototypical sedating/anticholinergic tertiary amine, hence its low-dose niche in migraine, neuropathic pain and insomnia; like all TCAs it is cardiotoxic in overdose, so it is avoided first-line in suicide-risk patients. Desipramine and protriptyline are activating secondary amines; nortriptyline is the better-tolerated secondary amine.","meds":["desipramine","amitriptyline","protriptyline","nortriptyline"],"focus":"sedation/anticholinergic / low-dose pain use","source":{"name":"Amitriptyline product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"amitriptyline"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_3_8","stem":"Which tetracyclic antidepressant — functionally a selective-noradrenergic TCA — has a long half-life and a notably HIGH seizure risk (dose- and accumulation-dependent), plus a relatively common skin rash?","options":["Nortriptyline","Desipramine","Doxepin","Maprotiline"],"answer":"Maprotiline","explanation":"Maprotiline is a tetracyclic that behaves like a selective-NE TCA; its long half-life (~43 h) and strong seizure-threshold lowering give it a high seizure risk, so titrate slowly and cap the dose. A skin rash is a recognized, relatively common effect. Nortriptyline, desipramine and doxepin do not share this high seizure/rash profile.","meds":["nortriptyline","desipramine","doxepin","maprotiline"],"focus":"tetracyclic seizure risk / rash","source":{"name":"Maprotiline product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"maprotiline"}],"antidepressants:4":[{"id":"rev_antidepressants_4_1","stem":"Which irreversible MAOI is a hydrazine that can deplete pyridoxine (vitamin B6) — causing peripheral neuropathy — and carries a distinct hepatotoxicity risk?","options":["Phenelzine","Tranylcypromine","Selegiline","Moclobemide"],"answer":"Phenelzine","explanation":"Phenelzine is a hydrazine MAOI; its hydrazine structure can deplete B6 (peripheral neuropathy) and cause hepatotoxicity. It is also the more sedating/anxiolytic classic MAOI. Tranylcypromine (amphetamine-like, non-hydrazine) and selegiline do not cause B6-depletion neuropathy; moclobemide is a reversible RIMA.","meds":["phenelzine","tranylcypromine","selegiline","moclobemide"],"focus":"hydrazine: B6 depletion / hepatotoxicity","source":{"name":"Phenelzine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"phenelzine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_4_2","stem":"Which irreversible MAOI has an amphetamine-like structure, making it activating (prominent insomnia — dose early) with some dependence/abuse potential and LESS weight gain than the sedating hydrazine MAOI?","options":["Phenelzine","Tranylcypromine","Selegiline","Moclobemide"],"answer":"Tranylcypromine","explanation":"Tranylcypromine is structurally amphetamine-like: activating, causing insomnia, and carrying some abuse potential, with less weight gain than phenelzine (the classic contrast pair — tranylcypromine activating/less weight; phenelzine sedating/more weight). Selegiline is MAO-B–selective at low dose; moclobemide is a RIMA.","meds":["phenelzine","tranylcypromine","selegiline","moclobemide"],"focus":"amphetamine-like activation / abuse potential","source":{"name":"Tranylcypromine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"tranylcypromine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_4_3","stem":"Which MAOI is MAO-B–selective at low dose and, in its low-dose transdermal patch (6 mg/24 h), bypasses first-pass gut MAO-A so that NO dietary tyramine restriction is required — though selectivity is lost (and the diet returns) at higher doses?","options":["Phenelzine","Tranylcypromine","Moclobemide","Selegiline"],"answer":"Selegiline","explanation":"Selegiline is MAO-B–selective at low dose; the 6 mg/24 h patch spares gut MAO-A (no diet needed), but 9–12 mg/24 h or high oral doses inhibit MAO-A and reinstate the diet. It is metabolized to l-amphetamine/l-methamphetamine (insomnia/activation). Crucially, its serotonin-syndrome contraindications apply at ANY dose or route. Phenelzine and tranylcypromine require the diet at all doses; moclobemide is a RIMA.","meds":["phenelzine","tranylcypromine","moclobemide","selegiline"],"focus":"MAO-B selectivity / transdermal diet-sparing","source":{"name":"Selegiline transdermal (Emsam) monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"selegiline"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_4_4","stem":"A patient with treatment-resistant depression and acute suicidal ideation needs a rapid-acting agent. Which is an intranasal NMDA-receptor antagonist that must be given in-clinic under a REMS-type program with ≥2 hours of monitoring for sedation, dissociation and blood-pressure rise?","options":["Esketamine","Brexanolone","Zuranolone","Tranylcypromine"],"answer":"Esketamine","explanation":"Esketamine (intranasal S-ketamine) is an NMDA antagonist producing an antidepressant effect within hours; it is used for treatment-resistant depression and MDD with acute suicidality and requires supervised in-clinic dosing (≥2 h monitoring, REMS), always paired with an oral antidepressant. Brexanolone and zuranolone are GABA-A neurosteroids for postpartum depression; tranylcypromine is a slow-onset MAOI.","meds":["esketamine","brexanolone","zuranolone","tranylcypromine"],"focus":"NMDA antagonist / rapid-acting / monitored dosing","source":{"name":"Esketamine (Spravato) label","origin":"openfda"},"answerId":"esketamine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_4_5","stem":"Which agent for postpartum depression is a neurosteroid (GABA-A positive allosteric modulator) given as a single continuous 60-hour IV infusion in a certified setting with continuous pulse-oximetry, because of a risk of excessive sedation and sudden loss of consciousness?","options":["Zuranolone","Brexanolone","Esketamine","Phenelzine"],"answer":"Brexanolone","explanation":"Brexanolone (IV allopregnanolone) was the first drug approved specifically for postpartum depression; its 60-h monitored infusion with continuous pulse-oximetry addresses the risk of excessive sedation and sudden loss of consciousness. Zuranolone is the ORAL neurosteroid successor; esketamine is intranasal for TRD; phenelzine is an MAOI.","meds":["zuranolone","brexanolone","esketamine","phenelzine"],"focus":"IV neurosteroid / continuous monitoring","source":{"name":"Brexanolone (Zulresso) label","origin":"openfda"},"answerId":"brexanolone"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_4_6","stem":"Which rapid-acting neurosteroid for postpartum depression is taken ORALLY as a finite 14-day course at home (in the evening, with fatty food; no driving for ≥12 h), rather than as a monitored infusion or a nasal spray?","options":["Zuranolone","Brexanolone","Esketamine","Selegiline"],"answer":"Zuranolone","explanation":"Zuranolone is an oral GABA-A-modulating neurosteroid given as a self-administered 14-day course — the practical outpatient counterpart to IV brexanolone — with benefit by roughly day 3. It is dosed in the evening with fatty food and prohibits driving for ≥12 h (sedation). Brexanolone is IV; esketamine is intranasal; selegiline is an MAOI.","meds":["zuranolone","brexanolone","esketamine","selegiline"],"focus":"oral finite-course neurosteroid (PPD)","source":{"name":"Zuranolone (Zurzuvae) label","origin":"openfda"},"answerId":"zuranolone"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_4_7","stem":"Between the two classic irreversible non-selective MAOIs, which is the MORE sedating and anxiolytic and causes MORE weight gain — historically favoured for atypical/anxious depression?","options":["Selegiline","Moclobemide","Phenelzine","Tranylcypromine"],"answer":"Phenelzine","explanation":"Phenelzine is the sedating, anxiolytic, weight-gaining MAOI (historically used for atypical/anxious depression), in contrast to activating, weight-sparing tranylcypromine. Selegiline (MAO-B–selective) and moclobemide (RIMA) are the diet-sparing alternatives, not the sedating hydrazine.","meds":["selegiline","moclobemide","phenelzine","tranylcypromine"],"focus":"phenelzine sedation/weight vs tranylcypromine activation","source":{"name":"Phenelzine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"phenelzine"},{"id":"rev_antidepressants_4_8","stem":"Which agent is contraindicated in patients with aneurysmal vascular disease, an arteriovenous malformation, or a history of intracerebral hemorrhage, because it transiently raises blood pressure after each dose?","options":["Zuranolone","Brexanolone","Esketamine","Selegiline"],"answer":"Esketamine","explanation":"Esketamine transiently raises blood pressure after dosing, so it is contraindicated in aneurysmal vascular disease, AVM and prior intracerebral hemorrhage, and BP is monitored at each visit. Zuranolone and brexanolone (neurosteroids) and selegiline do not carry this vascular contraindication.","meds":["zuranolone","brexanolone","esketamine","selegiline"],"focus":"BP elevation / vascular contraindication","source":{"name":"Esketamine (Spravato) label","origin":"openfda"},"answerId":"esketamine"}],"antipsychotics:0":[{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_0_1","stem":"A 24-year-old woman started on a first-line SGA develops amenorrhea, galactorrhea and cogwheel rigidity within a few weeks. Which agent — the most D2-potent of the SGAs — best explains BOTH the hyperprolactinemia and the extrapyramidal signs?","options":["Risperidone","Olanzapine","Quetiapine","Aripiprazole"],"answer":"Risperidone","explanation":"Risperidone is the most D2-potent SGA, so at usual doses it produces the most dose-dependent EPS and the most hyperprolactinemia of the atypicals — at higher doses it behaves like a high-potency FGA. Olanzapine and quetiapine both have loose/low D2 occupancy (low EPS, low prolactin), and aripiprazole is a partial agonist that is prolactin-sparing (it can even lower prolactin). The galactorrhea-plus-EPS picture points squarely to risperidone.","meds":["risperidone","olanzapine","quetiapine","aripiprazole"],"focus":"risperidone = most EPS + most hyperprolactinemia of the SGAs","source":{"name":"Risperidone monograph (dose-dependent EPS and hyperprolactinemia)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"risperidone"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_0_2","stem":"A 22-year-old man with a first episode of psychosis gains 9 kg over three months with new dyslipidemia and impaired fasting glucose. Which first-line SGA is, along with clozapine, among the WORST for weight gain and metabolic syndrome?","options":["Aripiprazole","Olanzapine","Quetiapine","Risperidone"],"answer":"Olanzapine","explanation":"Olanzapine's broad H1, muscarinic and 5-HT2C blockade makes it — with clozapine — one of the two highest metabolic-risk antipsychotics: marked weight gain, dyslipidemia and hyperglycemia/DKA. Aripiprazole is essentially weight- and prolactin-neutral, quetiapine carries only moderate metabolic risk, and risperidone is intermediate. Olanzapine buys high efficacy and strong sedation at the cost of the worst metabolic burden of the first-line group.","meds":["aripiprazole","olanzapine","quetiapine","risperidone"],"focus":"olanzapine = worst metabolic risk (with clozapine)","source":{"name":"Olanzapine monograph (metabolic warnings; hyperglycemia/DKA)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"olanzapine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_0_3","stem":"A patient with Parkinson disease develops distressing visual hallucinations. If a standard antipsychotic must be used, which first-line SGA is preferred because its loose D2 binding gives the LOWEST EPS and prolactin, minimizing worsening of motor symptoms?","options":["Haloperidol","Risperidone","Quetiapine","Olanzapine"],"answer":"Quetiapine","explanation":"Quetiapine has the loosest/lowest D2 occupancy of these agents, giving the lowest EPS and prolactin — which is why it is a traditional go-to when psychosis must be treated in Parkinson disease or in EPS-prone patients. Haloperidol (high-potency FGA) and risperidone (most D2-potent SGA) would both worsen parkinsonism, and olanzapine carries more anticholinergic and metabolic burden. Quetiapine is also very sedating via potent H1.","meds":["haloperidol","risperidone","quetiapine","olanzapine"],"focus":"quetiapine = lowest EPS/prolactin (Parkinson disease psychosis)","source":{"name":"CANMAT/monograph — low-EPS choice in Parkinson disease psychosis","origin":"canmat"},"answerId":"quetiapine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_0_4","stem":"A young man started on an antipsychotic becomes restless and unable to sit still (akathisia), stays activated, and later discloses new compulsive online gambling. Which first-line agent — a D2/D3 partial agonist — best fits this activating, prolactin-sparing, impulse-control profile?","options":["Olanzapine","Quetiapine","Haloperidol","Aripiprazole"],"answer":"Aripiprazole","explanation":"Aripiprazole is the prototype D2/D3 PARTIAL agonist (\"dopamine system stabilizer\"): weight- and prolactin-neutral and low-sedation, but characteristically activating with prominent akathisia, and it carries the dopamine-agonist impulse-control warning (pathological gambling, hypersexuality, compulsive shopping/eating). Olanzapine and quetiapine are sedating antagonists, and haloperidol causes EPS and raises prolactin rather than activation and gambling. Ask specifically about impulse-control urges.","meds":["olanzapine","quetiapine","haloperidol","aripiprazole"],"focus":"aripiprazole = partial agonist (akathisia/activation + impulse-control)","source":{"name":"Aripiprazole monograph (impulse-control disorders; akathisia)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"aripiprazole"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_0_5","stem":"An agitated inpatient needs a high-potency dopamine blocker, and the team also wants a long-acting depot for a patient with poor adherence. Which of these first-line-row agents is the prototype HIGH-potency drug — maximal EPS, minimal sedation/anticholinergic effect — with a decanoate LAI and an IV form notorious for torsades?","options":["Haloperidol","Quetiapine","Olanzapine","Aripiprazole"],"answer":"Haloperidol","explanation":"Haloperidol is the high-potency butyrophenone benchmark: very high D2 affinity with little H1/M1 activity, so EPS dominate while sedation and anticholinergic effects are minimal. It is available as a decanoate depot (about every 4 weeks) for non-adherence, and IV haloperidol carries the highest torsades risk (telemetry required). Quetiapine, olanzapine and aripiprazole are all SGAs and are not the high-potency, EPS-heavy, decanoate-plus-IV-torsades agent described.","meds":["haloperidol","quetiapine","olanzapine","aripiprazole"],"focus":"haloperidol = high-potency FGA (decanoate LAI; IV torsades)","source":{"name":"Haloperidol monograph (QT/torsades with IV; decanoate)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"haloperidol"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_0_6","stem":"A patient with obesity, dyslipidemia and a strong family history of type 2 diabetes needs an antipsychotic that is least likely to worsen weight, glucose and lipids. Among these first-line options, which is the most metabolically favourable choice?","options":["Olanzapine","Quetiapine","Aripiprazole","Risperidone"],"answer":"Aripiprazole","explanation":"Aripiprazole's partial-agonist profile with low H1/muscarinic activity makes it weight- and prolactin-neutral — the best metabolic pick here. Olanzapine is among the two worst SGAs metabolically, quetiapine carries moderate metabolic risk, and risperidone is intermediate. The trade-off for aripiprazole's metabolic advantage is its activating, akathisia-prone character rather than sedation or weight gain.","meds":["olanzapine","quetiapine","aripiprazole","risperidone"],"focus":"aripiprazole = metabolically favourable (lowest weight/prolactin)","source":{"name":"Aripiprazole monograph (weight/prolactin-neutral profile)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"aripiprazole"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_0_7","stem":"A distressed patient with insomnia asks to \"just stay on the low dose that helps me sleep.\" Which first-line agent is so sedating (via potent H1) that low doses are commonly — and problematically — used off-label as a hypnotic, with a dose-dependent identity that only becomes antipsychotic at high doses?","options":["Quetiapine","Aripiprazole","Risperidone","Haloperidol"],"answer":"Quetiapine","explanation":"Quetiapine has a dose-effect ladder: low dose is sedative/anxiolytic (potent H1), mid dose is antidepressant (norquetiapine NET inhibition), and only high dose is reliably antipsychotic — which is why low-dose off-label use as a sleep aid is common but discouraged. Aripiprazole is activating (worsens insomnia), risperidone is only modestly sedating, and haloperidol has minimal H1 effect. Quetiapine is the sedation outlier here.","meds":["quetiapine","aripiprazole","risperidone","haloperidol"],"focus":"quetiapine = potent H1 sedation / dose-dependent identity","source":{"name":"Quetiapine monograph (sedation; dose-effect ladder)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"quetiapine"}],"antipsychotics:1":[{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_1_1","stem":"A patient with hepatic impairment and heavy polypharmacy needs an SGA with minimal CYP drug interactions, and the team wants long-acting injectable options for adherence. Which next-line agent is the renally-cleared active 9-hydroxy metabolite of risperidone, available as monthly and every-3-month LAIs?","options":["Paliperidone","Lurasidone","Ziprasidone","Risperidone"],"answer":"Paliperidone","explanation":"Paliperidone IS 9-hydroxyrisperidone, excreted largely unchanged by the kidney — so it has few CYP interactions (useful with hepatic impairment or polypharmacy) but must be dose-reduced for renal function. Its LAIs (Sustenna monthly, Trinza every 3 months) are major adherence tools. Lurasidone and ziprasidone are CYP3A4-dependent oral agents with food requirements and no LAI. Risperidone is the parent drug, not the renally-cleared metabolite described.","meds":["paliperidone","lurasidone","ziprasidone","risperidone"],"focus":"paliperidone = renally-cleared risperidone metabolite (LAI options)","source":{"name":"Paliperidone monograph (renal clearance; Sustenna/Trinza LAIs)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"paliperidone"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_1_2","stem":"A patient with bipolar I depression who is metabolically vulnerable (obese, prediabetic) needs a well-tolerated antipsychotic. Which next-line SGA is a first-line choice for bipolar depression, is weight-/lipid-/glucose-favourable with low QT, but MUST be taken with a meal of at least 350 kcal for absorption?","options":["Ziprasidone","Lurasidone","Paliperidone","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Lurasidone","explanation":"Lurasidone is metabolically favourable (very low H1/muscarinic activity → weight-, lipid- and glucose-neutral, low prolactin, low QT) and a strong first-line agent for bipolar I depression — but its absorption depends on taking it with food (≥350 kcal), and as a CYP3A4 substrate it is contraindicated with strong 3A4 inhibitors/inducers and grapefruit. Ziprasidone also needs food but requires a larger meal and is the QT outlier; paliperidone raises prolactin; quetiapine is more sedating with moderate metabolic risk.","meds":["ziprasidone","lurasidone","paliperidone","quetiapine"],"focus":"lurasidone = bipolar depression; food ≥350 kcal; metabolically favourable","source":{"name":"Lurasidone monograph (food ≥350 kcal; bipolar depression; CYP3A4)","origin":"canmat"},"answerId":"lurasidone"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_1_3","stem":"A patient with a baseline QTc of 475 ms who is also on methadone needs an antipsychotic. Which next-line SGA has the GREATEST QT-prolonging effect of the class — its defining caution — and should therefore be avoided here?","options":["Paliperidone","Lurasidone","Ziprasidone","Aripiprazole"],"answer":"Ziprasidone","explanation":"Ziprasidone produces the greatest QT prolongation of the SGAs, with torsades risk, so it is exactly the wrong choice at QTc 475 ms on methadone. Paliperidone has only modest QT effect, lurasidone is low-QT, and aripiprazole has no notable QT signal — any of these is a safer cardiac option. Recognizing ziprasidone as the QT outlier (and correcting electrolytes/avoiding other QT drugs) is the key point.","meds":["paliperidone","lurasidone","ziprasidone","aripiprazole"],"focus":"ziprasidone = greatest QT prolongation of the SGAs","source":{"name":"Ziprasidone monograph (greatest QT prolongation of SGAs)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"ziprasidone"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_1_4","stem":"Two SGAs in this next-line row must be taken with food or absorption fails. Which one requires the LARGER meal — at least 500 kcal — and is also the agent most associated with QT prolongation, making a skipped-meal \"treatment failure\" doubly important to counsel about?","options":["Lurasidone","Ziprasidone","Paliperidone"],"answer":"Ziprasidone","explanation":"Both lurasidone and ziprasidone depend on food, but ziprasidone requires the larger meal (≥500 kcal versus lurasidone's ≥350 kcal); on an empty stomach its absorption roughly halves — a classic cause of apparent treatment failure. Ziprasidone is also the QT-prolongation outlier of the SGAs. Paliperidone (OROS tablet) has no caloric food requirement. The teaching point is the 500-vs-350 kcal contrast and ziprasidone's dual food-plus-QT caution.","meds":["lurasidone","ziprasidone","paliperidone"],"focus":"ziprasidone food ≥500 kcal (vs lurasidone ≥350 kcal)","source":{"name":"Ziprasidone monograph (≥500 kcal food requirement)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"ziprasidone"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_1_5","stem":"A woman on a next-line SGA develops galactorrhea and menstrual irregularity. Which agent in this row is most likely responsible, because its receptor profile mirrors risperidone's with dose-dependent hyperprolactinemia and EPS?","options":["Ziprasidone","Lurasidone","Paliperidone"],"answer":"Paliperidone","explanation":"Paliperidone is 9-hydroxyrisperidone, so it shares risperidone's dose-dependent EPS and hyperprolactinemia — galactorrhea and amenorrhea are expected class effects. Lurasidone and ziprasidone are both low-prolactin and metabolically favourable, so neither typically causes marked hyperprolactinemia. When prolactin-related symptoms appear in this row, paliperidone is the culprit.","meds":["ziprasidone","lurasidone","paliperidone"],"focus":"paliperidone = hyperprolactinemia (mirrors risperidone)","source":{"name":"Paliperidone monograph (hyperprolactinemia)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"paliperidone"}],"antipsychotics:2":[{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_2_1","stem":"A 29-year-old man with schizophrenia remains floridly psychotic after two adequate antipsychotic trials with confirmed adherence. Which agent in this row is the only one proven superior for treatment-resistant schizophrenia (and to reduce suicidality), obligating registry-enforced ANC monitoring — weekly for 6 months, then every 2 weeks to 12 months, then every 4 weeks?","options":["Clozapine","Olanzapine","Quetiapine","Risperidone"],"answer":"Clozapine","explanation":"Two failed adequate trials define treatment-resistant schizophrenia, and clozapine is uniquely effective there and uniquely anti-suicidal. Because of agranulocytosis it mandates registry ANC monitoring (weekly ×6 months → every 2 weeks to 12 months → every 4 weeks). Beyond the blood count, remember its early killers: myocarditis in the first 6–8 weeks and severe constipation progressing to ileus. Olanzapine, quetiapine and risperidone are reasonable general agents but none is a resistance-specific drug and none carries mandatory ANC surveillance.","meds":["clozapine","olanzapine","quetiapine","risperidone"],"focus":"clozapine = treatment-resistant schizophrenia + mandatory ANC monitoring","source":{"name":"Clozapine monograph (boxed warning; ANC schedule)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"clozapine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_2_2","stem":"A patient did well on a dopamine partial agonist but could not tolerate the akathisia. Which agent in this newer row is also a D2 partial agonist but is engineered for better tolerability (lower D2 intrinsic activity → less activation/akathisia than aripiprazole) and is approved as an ADJUNCT for major depressive disorder?","options":["Cariprazine","Brexpiprazole","Aripiprazole","Asenapine"],"answer":"Brexpiprazole","explanation":"Brexpiprazole is a D2 partial agonist with lower intrinsic activity than aripiprazole, giving less activation and less akathisia (at the cost of slightly more weight gain), and it is approved as an adjunct in MDD. Cariprazine is a partial agonist too but is D3-preferring and more EPS/akathisia-prone. Aripiprazole is the more activating comparator being replaced here, and asenapine is a sublingual antagonist, not a partial agonist.","meds":["cariprazine","brexpiprazole","aripiprazole","asenapine"],"focus":"brexpiprazole = partial agonist with less akathisia; adjunct MDD","source":{"name":"Brexpiprazole monograph (lower akathisia; adjunctive MDD)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"brexpiprazole"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_2_3","stem":"A clinician wants a partial agonist that covers BOTH poles of bipolar I (mania/mixed and depression) and may help negative symptoms, but warns the patient that dose changes and side effects take weeks to appear or resolve. Which agent — the most D3-selective antipsychotic, with active metabolites lasting weeks — is described?","options":["Brexpiprazole","Asenapine","Cariprazine","Clozapine"],"answer":"Cariprazine","explanation":"Cariprazine is the D3-preferring D2/D3 partial agonist (theoretical benefit for negative symptoms/anhedonia) and is distinctive among partial agonists for covering both mania/mixed AND bipolar depression. Its very long-lived active metabolites mean slow onset and slow offset — effects and side effects persist for weeks after a dose change or discontinuation. Brexpiprazole lacks the dual bipolar coverage and long-metabolite tail; asenapine and clozapine are antagonists, not D3-preferring partial agonists.","meds":["brexpiprazole","asenapine","cariprazine","clozapine"],"focus":"cariprazine = D3-preferring, dual bipolar coverage, weeks-long metabolites","source":{"name":"Cariprazine monograph (D3 preference; long-lived metabolites)","origin":"canmat"},"answerId":"cariprazine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_2_4","stem":"A patient reports tongue numbness and an odd taste after each dose of a new antipsychotic, and is counselled to avoid food and drink for 10 minutes after taking it. Which agent — the only one given by a route where swallowing destroys bioavailability — is this, and what route is it?","options":["Asenapine","Cariprazine","Brexpiprazole","Clozapine"],"answer":"Asenapine","explanation":"Asenapine is the only SUBLINGUAL antipsychotic: extensive first-pass metabolism means swallowing it destroys bioavailability, so it is placed under the tongue and dissolved, with no food or drink for 10 minutes. Oral hypoesthesia (tongue numbness) and altered taste are characteristic, and serious hypersensitivity (angioedema/anaphylaxis) can occur even with the first dose. Cariprazine, brexpiprazole and clozapine are all swallowed oral agents.","meds":["asenapine","cariprazine","brexpiprazole","clozapine"],"focus":"asenapine = only sublingual antipsychotic (no food/drink ×10 min)","source":{"name":"Asenapine monograph (sublingual administration; oral hypoesthesia)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"asenapine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_2_5","stem":"Three weeks after starting a new antipsychotic, a young man develops chest pain, tachycardia, fatigue and a fever, with rising troponin and CRP. Which agent in this row demands surveillance for exactly this early complication?","options":["Cariprazine","Clozapine","Asenapine","Brexpiprazole"],"answer":"Clozapine","explanation":"Clozapine-induced myocarditis peaks in the first 6–8 weeks and presents with tachycardia, chest pain, fever, fatigue and rising troponin/CRP — a can't-miss early killer that warrants active surveillance (symptoms, heart rate, troponin/CRP) during initiation. This is separate from the mandatory ANC monitoring for agranulocytosis and from severe constipation/ileus, its other early hazards. Cariprazine, asenapine and brexpiprazole do not carry this early myocarditis signal.","meds":["cariprazine","clozapine","asenapine","brexpiprazole"],"focus":"clozapine = early myocarditis (first 6–8 weeks)","source":{"name":"Clozapine monograph (myocarditis/cardiomyopathy warning)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"clozapine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_2_6","stem":"A patient with residual anhedonia and prominent negative symptoms is being considered for a partial agonist, and the team specifically wants the one theorized to help negative symptoms through the highest D3 selectivity of the class. Which agent is that?","options":["Asenapine","Brexpiprazole","Clozapine","Cariprazine"],"answer":"Cariprazine","explanation":"Cariprazine is the most D3-selective antipsychotic; its D3 preference is the basis for the theorized benefit in negative symptoms and anhedonia, distinguishing it from brexpiprazole (a tolerability-optimized D2 partial agonist without D3 preference). Asenapine and clozapine are broad antagonists rather than D3-preferring partial agonists. This contrast — brexpiprazole for tolerability versus cariprazine for D3-driven negative-symptom coverage — is the high-yield discriminator between the two newer partial agonists.","meds":["asenapine","brexpiprazole","clozapine","cariprazine"],"focus":"cariprazine = highest D3 selectivity (negative symptoms)","source":{"name":"Cariprazine monograph (D3-preferring partial agonism)","origin":"canmat"},"answerId":"cariprazine"}],"antipsychotics:3":[{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_3_1","stem":"An older FGA causes marked sedation, orthostatic hypotension, dry mouth and photosensitivity, with comparatively LESS EPS than high-potency agents; long-term high doses can cause blue-grey skin and cholestatic jaundice. Which classic low-potency phenothiazine prototype is this?","options":["Chlorpromazine","Fluphenazine","Perphenazine","Loxapine"],"answer":"Chlorpromazine","explanation":"Chlorpromazine is the prototype LOW-potency phenothiazine: strong H1 (sedation), M1 (anticholinergic) and α1 (orthostasis) blockade with comparatively less EPS, plus its signature photosensitivity, cholestatic jaundice and lowered seizure threshold. Fluphenazine is high-potency (EPS-heavy, low sedation), perphenazine is mid-potency, and loxapine is a mid-potency dibenzoxazepine. Potency, not chemistry, predicts this sedating/hypotensive/anticholinergic pattern.","meds":["chlorpromazine","fluphenazine","perphenazine","loxapine"],"focus":"chlorpromazine = low-potency prototype (sedation/orthostasis/photosensitivity)","source":{"name":"Chlorpromazine monograph (low-potency profile; photosensitivity; jaundice)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"chlorpromazine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_3_2","stem":"A non-adherent patient stabilized on an oral high-potency phenothiazine is switched to a decanoate depot. Which of these agents is the high-potency phenothiazine whose decanoate is dosed every 2–3 weeks — a SHORTER interval than haloperidol decanoate's ~4 weeks?","options":["Chlorpromazine","Fluphenazine","Loxapine","Zuclopenthixol"],"answer":"Fluphenazine","explanation":"Fluphenazine is a high-potency piperazine phenothiazine (lots of EPS, little sedation/anticholinergic effect) whose decanoate LAI is given roughly every 2–3 weeks — a shorter dosing interval than haloperidol decanoate's ~4 weeks, a common exam contrast. Chlorpromazine is low-potency and not a standard depot, loxapine's niche is the inhaled form, and zuclopenthixol's decanoate is a thioxanthene depot rather than a phenothiazine one.","meds":["chlorpromazine","fluphenazine","loxapine","zuclopenthixol"],"focus":"fluphenazine = high-potency; decanoate q2–3 wk (shorter than haloperidol)","source":{"name":"Fluphenazine monograph (decanoate dosing interval)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"fluphenazine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_3_3","stem":"Which of these first-generation agents was the FGA comparator in the CATIE effectiveness trial, where this mid-potency phenothiazine performed comparably to several SGAs at far lower cost — challenging the assumption that newer equals better?","options":["Loxapine","Fluphenazine","Perphenazine","Chlorpromazine"],"answer":"Perphenazine","explanation":"Perphenazine, a mid-potency piperazine phenothiazine, was the FGA arm in CATIE and was roughly as effective as several SGAs while being highly cost-effective. Its side-effect profile sits between chlorpromazine (low-potency, sedating) and haloperidol/fluphenazine (high-potency, EPS-heavy): moderate EPS, moderate sedation and autonomic effects. Loxapine, fluphenazine and chlorpromazine were not the CATIE FGA benchmark.","meds":["loxapine","fluphenazine","perphenazine","chlorpromazine"],"focus":"perphenazine = CATIE FGA benchmark (mid-potency)","source":{"name":"CATIE trial (perphenazine as FGA comparator)","origin":"canmat"},"answerId":"perphenazine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_3_4","stem":"For rapid in-clinic control of acute agitation, which of these FGAs is available as a single-dose INHALED formulation (Adasuve) that can cause bronchospasm — mandating an on-hand bronchodilator and making it contraindicated in asthma or COPD?","options":["Perphenazine","Loxapine","Chlorpromazine","Fluphenazine"],"answer":"Loxapine","explanation":"Loxapine is a mid-potency dibenzoxazepine, but the high-yield point is its inhaled formulation (Adasuve) for rapid single-dose control of agitation — which can cause bronchospasm, so a short-acting bronchodilator must be available and it is contraindicated in asthma/COPD or active bronchospasm. Perphenazine, chlorpromazine and fluphenazine have no inhaled route or bronchospasm caveat.","meds":["perphenazine","loxapine","chlorpromazine","fluphenazine"],"focus":"loxapine = inhaled route (bronchospasm; contraindicated asthma/COPD)","source":{"name":"Inhaled loxapine (Adasuve) monograph (bronchospasm warning)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"loxapine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_3_5","stem":"An acutely agitated, floridly psychotic patient needs an injection that covers about 2–3 days to bridge to oral or depot therapy — but must NOT be used for maintenance. Which Canadian thioxanthene's short-acting ACETATE ester (Acuphase) fills this niche?","options":["Zuclopenthixol","Flupenthixol","Fluphenazine","Perphenazine"],"answer":"Zuclopenthixol","explanation":"Zuclopenthixol acetate (Acuphase) is a Canadian tool for the acutely disturbed patient: one injection covers roughly 2–3 days (~72 h) to bridge to oral or depot treatment, and it is explicitly NOT a maintenance depot. Its sibling flupenthixol has only oral and decanoate forms (no acetate), while fluphenazine and perphenazine are phenothiazines. The acetate-for-acute-only concept is the key.","meds":["zuclopenthixol","flupenthixol","fluphenazine","perphenazine"],"focus":"zuclopenthixol acetate (Acuphase) = short-acting, acute-only","source":{"name":"Zuclopenthixol acetate (Acuphase) monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"zuclopenthixol"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_3_6","stem":"Which Canada-specific thioxanthene is distinctive because at LOW doses it is activating/mildly antidepressant, while higher doses are antipsychotic — and it is available only as oral tablets plus a decanoate depot (no short-acting acetate)?","options":["Zuclopenthixol","Chlorpromazine","Perphenazine","Flupenthixol"],"answer":"Flupenthixol","explanation":"Flupenthixol is the thioxanthene with a low-dose activating/antidepressant quirk (historically used for depression/anxiety) that becomes antipsychotic at higher doses; it comes as oral tablets and a decanoate depot (q2–3 weeks) but has no acetate. Its sibling zuclopenthixol adds the short-acting Acuphase acetate — the distinguishing difference between the two thioxanthenes. Chlorpromazine and perphenazine are phenothiazines without this low-dose antidepressant profile.","meds":["zuclopenthixol","chlorpromazine","perphenazine","flupenthixol"],"focus":"flupenthixol = low-dose activating/antidepressant; oral + decanoate only","source":{"name":"Flupenthixol monograph (low-dose activating use; oral + decanoate)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"flupenthixol"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_3_7","stem":"Two of these phenothiazines share the same chemical family but opposite side-effect patterns. Which one, because it is HIGH-potency, causes the most EPS and acute dystonia with little sedation — the opposite of low-potency chlorpromazine — illustrating that potency, not chemistry, predicts the profile?","options":["Chlorpromazine","Perphenazine","Fluphenazine","Loxapine"],"answer":"Fluphenazine","explanation":"Fluphenazine is a high-potency phenothiazine: very high D2 affinity with low H1/M1 activity means EPS and acute dystonia dominate while sedation and anticholinergic effects are minimal — the mirror image of low-potency chlorpromazine, even though both are phenothiazines. Perphenazine is intermediate and loxapine is a mid-potency dibenzoxazepine. The lesson is that within one chemical family, potency drives the EPS-versus-sedation trade-off.","meds":["chlorpromazine","perphenazine","fluphenazine","loxapine"],"focus":"high- vs low-potency: fluphenazine = most EPS, least sedation","source":{"name":"Fluphenazine monograph (high-potency EPS profile)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"fluphenazine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_3_8","stem":"Depot esters differ by drug. Which of these agents is unique in offering BOTH a short-acting acetate for acute management AND a maintenance decanoate depot (three ester forms in total: oral, acetate, decanoate)?","options":["Zuclopenthixol","Flupenthixol","Fluphenazine","Pipotiazine"],"answer":"Zuclopenthixol","explanation":"Zuclopenthixol is distinctive for three ester forms: oral, a short-acting acetate (Acuphase, ~72 h for acute disturbance) and a maintenance decanoate depot (q2–4 weeks) — no other agent here spans acute-acetate plus maintenance-decanoate. Flupenthixol and fluphenazine have oral plus decanoate only (no acetate), and pipotiazine is a phenothiazine offered essentially only as a palmitate LAI. Matching drug to available ester is the discrimination.","meds":["zuclopenthixol","flupenthixol","fluphenazine","pipotiazine"],"focus":"zuclopenthixol = both acetate (acute) and decanoate (maintenance)","source":{"name":"Zuclopenthixol monograph (acetate + decanoate esters)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"zuclopenthixol"}],"antipsychotics:4":[{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_4_1","stem":"Which of these legacy agents is a HIGH-potency piperazine phenothiazine that is EPS-heavy with little sedation or anticholinergic effect — behaving much like haloperidol — in contrast to low-potency, sedating chlorpromazine of the same chemical family?","options":["Trifluoperazine","Chlorpromazine","Methotrimeprazine","Prochlorperazine"],"answer":"Trifluoperazine","explanation":"Trifluoperazine is a high-potency piperazine phenothiazine: EPS-predominant with minimal sedation/anticholinergic burden, so it behaves like haloperidol/fluphenazine despite being a phenothiazine. Chlorpromazine and methotrimeprazine are low-potency (very sedating, hypotensive), and prochlorperazine is used mainly as an antiemetic. The point is that potency, not the phenothiazine chemistry, predicts the side-effect pattern.","meds":["trifluoperazine","chlorpromazine","methotrimeprazine","prochlorperazine"],"focus":"trifluoperazine = high-potency phenothiazine (behaves like haloperidol)","source":{"name":"Trifluoperazine monograph (high-potency EPS profile)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"trifluoperazine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_4_2","stem":"A palliative-care team needs a single agent that provides sedation, analgesia AND antiemesis for terminal restlessness, intractable nausea and pain, often given subcutaneously. Which low-potency phenothiazine (levomepromazine) — dose-limited by profound sedation and marked orthostasis — fits this role?","options":["Trifluoperazine","Methotrimeprazine","Pimozide","Droperidol"],"answer":"Methotrimeprazine","explanation":"Methotrimeprazine (levomepromazine) is a low-potency phenothiazine that is a palliative-care workhorse: it combines profound sedation with genuine analgesic and antiemetic activity, and is frequently given subcutaneously for terminal agitation, nausea and pain. Its dose-limiting effects are marked orthostatic hypotension and sedation, while EPS are comparatively mild (low-potency). Trifluoperazine is high-potency/EPS-heavy, and pimozide and droperidol are not the sedative-analgesic-antiemetic palliative agent.","meds":["trifluoperazine","methotrimeprazine","pimozide","droperidol"],"focus":"methotrimeprazine = palliative sedation + analgesia + antiemesis","source":{"name":"Methotrimeprazine (levomepromazine) monograph (palliative use)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"methotrimeprazine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_4_3","stem":"Which diphenylbutylpiperidine, reserved largely for Tourette syndrome refractory to other agents, has the strongest QT signal of the FGAs — dose-dependent prolongation with torsades and reported sudden death — requiring ECG-driven dosing?","options":["Droperidol","Trifluoperazine","Pimozide","Prochlorperazine"],"answer":"Pimozide","explanation":"Pimozide is the QT champion among FGAs: it blocks cardiac calcium channels, causing marked dose-dependent QT prolongation with torsades and reported sudden death, so baseline and follow-up ECGs are mandatory. Its niche is refractory Tourette syndrome. Droperidol also prolongs QT but is a short-acting butyrophenone used for acute agitation/PONV, trifluoperazine is a high-potency antipsychotic phenothiazine, and prochlorperazine is used mainly as an antiemetic — none matches pimozide's ECG-driven, Tourette-reserved, torsades profile.","meds":["droperidol","trifluoperazine","pimozide","prochlorperazine"],"focus":"pimozide = strongest QT/torsades FGA (Tourette niche; ECG-driven)","source":{"name":"Pimozide monograph (QT prolongation; ECG-driven dosing)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"pimozide"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_4_4","stem":"A young woman given a single dose of a phenothiazine for nausea/vertigo in the ED develops an acute dystonic reaction (oculogyric crisis). Which agent — used mainly as an ANTIEMETIC (Stemetil) rather than for psychosis — is the classic culprit?","options":["Prochlorperazine","Pimozide","Droperidol","Trifluoperazine"],"answer":"Prochlorperazine","explanation":"Prochlorperazine is a piperazine phenothiazine used mainly as an antiemetic/anti-vertigo agent (Stemetil), and acute dystonic reactions can occur even after a single antiemetic dose — classically in young women — treated with an anticholinergic (benztropine) or diphenhydramine. It is the reminder that dopamine-blocking antiemetics carry EPS/TD risk. Pimozide and trifluoperazine are used for psychosis/Tourette, and droperidol, though also antiemetic, is defined by its QT risk rather than the single-dose dystonia teaching point.","meds":["prochlorperazine","pimozide","droperidol","trifluoperazine"],"focus":"prochlorperazine = antiemetic; acute dystonia from a single dose","source":{"name":"Prochlorperazine monograph (acute dystonic reactions)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"prochlorperazine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_4_5","stem":"In the ED, a fast-acting, titratable agent with a short (~2 h) half-life is wanted for acute agitation and for postoperative nausea/vomiting — but it carries a prominent torsades warning even at low antiemetic doses. Which short-acting butyrophenone (haloperidol's cousin) is this?","options":["Pimozide","Droperidol","Methotrimeprazine","Prochlorperazine"],"answer":"Droperidol","explanation":"Droperidol is haloperidol's short-acting butyrophenone cousin: fast onset and a ~2 h half-life make it useful for rapid, titratable control of agitation and for PONV, but it carries a prominent QT-prolongation/torsades warning even at low antiemetic doses — assess QT risk, correct K/Mg and monitor ECG. Pimozide is the oral, long-acting Tourette agent with QT risk, methotrimeprazine is the sedating palliative phenothiazine, and prochlorperazine's signature hazard is acute dystonia rather than torsades.","meds":["pimozide","droperidol","methotrimeprazine","prochlorperazine"],"focus":"droperidol = short-acting butyrophenone; QT/torsades at antiemetic doses","source":{"name":"Droperidol monograph (QT/torsades warning)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"droperidol"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_4_6","stem":"A Canadian patient with schizophrenia and poor adherence is to be maintained on a long-acting injectable. Which Canada-specific phenothiazine is used essentially only as a PALMITATE-ester depot (Piportil L4), dosed roughly every 4 weeks?","options":["Fluphenazine","Trifluoperazine","Pipotiazine","Methotrimeprazine"],"answer":"Pipotiazine","explanation":"Pipotiazine (Piportil L4) is a Canada-specific piperidine phenothiazine used essentially only as a maintenance depot, notable for its PALMITATE ester — distinguishing it from the decanoate depots (haloperidol, fluphenazine, zuclopenthixol, flupenthixol) — with roughly monthly (q4-week) dosing. Fluphenazine's depot is a decanoate, trifluoperazine is an oral high-potency agent, and methotrimeprazine is a sedating/analgesic palliative phenothiazine, not a maintenance LAI. Matching the palmitate ester to pipotiazine is the discrimination.","meds":["fluphenazine","trifluoperazine","pipotiazine","methotrimeprazine"],"focus":"pipotiazine = palmitate-ester LAI (≈ monthly; vs decanoates)","source":{"name":"Pipotiazine palmitate (Piportil L4) monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"pipotiazine"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_4_7","stem":"A novel-mechanism antipsychotic (US-only) achieves its effect with LOW absolute D2 occupancy (~40%) and a high 5-HT2A:D2 ratio plus SERT inhibition, giving unusually low EPS, low prolactin and low metabolic signal — and is approved across schizophrenia AND both bipolar I and II depression. Which agent is this?","options":["Pimavanserin","Lumateperone","Xanomeline–Trospium","Trifluoperazine"],"answer":"Lumateperone","explanation":"Lumateperone (Caplyta; US-only, not marketed in Canada) has a high 5-HT2A:D2 ratio with low absolute D2 occupancy (~40%) plus SERT inhibition, yielding low EPS, low prolactin and a low metabolic/weight signal — and it is uniquely approved across schizophrenia and both bipolar I and II depression, at a fixed single dose with food. Pimavanserin is a 5-HT2A inverse agonist for Parkinson psychosis, xanomeline–trospium is a muscarinic agonist with no D2 activity, and trifluoperazine is a classic high-potency D2 blocker.","meds":["pimavanserin","lumateperone","xanomeline_trospium","trifluoperazine"],"focus":"lumateperone = low D2 occupancy + SERT; schizophrenia + bipolar I/II depression","source":{"name":"Lumateperone (Caplyta) label (mechanism; indications)","origin":"dailymed"},"answerId":"lumateperone"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_4_8","stem":"A first-in-class antipsychotic (US-only) treats schizophrenia WITHOUT blocking dopamine at all — an M1/M4 muscarinic agonist paired with a peripherally-restricted muscarinic antagonist to limit cholinergic side effects — so it produces no EPS, no tardive dyskinesia from D2 blockade, and no prolactin elevation. Which agent is this?","options":["Xanomeline–Trospium","Lumateperone","Pimavanserin","Pimozide"],"answer":"Xanomeline–Trospium","explanation":"Xanomeline–trospium (Cobenfy, formerly KarXT; US-only) is the first antipsychotic approved for schizophrenia that does NOT block dopamine: xanomeline is an M1/M4 muscarinic agonist acting upstream of the dopamine synapse, and trospium is a peripherally-restricted muscarinic antagonist added purely to blunt peripheral cholinergic effects (nausea, GI, sweating) without reducing central efficacy. Because there is no D2 blockade, there is essentially no EPS, no D2-driven tardive dyskinesia and no hyperprolactinemia; its side effects are cholinergic/anticholinergic instead. Lumateperone still has some D2 activity, pimavanserin is a 5-HT2A inverse agonist, and pimozide is a potent D2 blocker.","meds":["xanomeline_trospium","lumateperone","pimavanserin","pimozide"],"focus":"xanomeline–trospium = muscarinic M1/M4 agonist, no D2 blockade","source":{"name":"Xanomeline–trospium (Cobenfy) label (muscarinic mechanism)","origin":"dailymed"},"answerId":"xanomeline_trospium"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_4_9","stem":"A patient with Parkinson disease develops hallucinations and delusions. Which US-only agent — a selective 5-HT2A INVERSE AGONIST with essentially no dopamine (D2) activity — treats the psychosis without worsening parkinsonian motor symptoms, while carrying a QT caution and the class boxed warning for dementia-related mortality?","options":["Lumateperone","Xanomeline–Trospium","Pimavanserin","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Pimavanserin","explanation":"Pimavanserin (Nuplazid; US-only) is a selective 5-HT2A inverse agonist with no D2 activity, purpose-built for Parkinson disease psychosis — it controls hallucinations/delusions without the motor worsening that D2-blocking antipsychotics cause. Its profile is dominated by QT prolongation and the class boxed warning for increased mortality in elderly dementia-related psychosis rather than EPS/metabolic effects. Lumateperone still has some D2 occupancy, xanomeline–trospium is a muscarinic agonist, and quetiapine (though low-EPS) still blocks D2.","meds":["lumateperone","xanomeline_trospium","pimavanserin","quetiapine"],"focus":"pimavanserin = 5-HT2A inverse agonist for Parkinson psychosis (no D2)","source":{"name":"Pimavanserin (Nuplazid) label (5-HT2A inverse agonist; PD psychosis)","origin":"dailymed"},"answerId":"pimavanserin"},{"id":"rev_antipsychotics_4_10","stem":"A patient on an oral FGA for refractory Tourette syndrome is about to start clarithromycin, and the pharmacist flags a dangerous interaction. Which agent is contraindicated with macrolides, azole antifungals, protease inhibitors and grapefruit juice because CYP3A4 inhibition raises its level and dangerously prolongs the QT interval?","options":["Droperidol","Pimavanserin","Trifluoperazine","Pimozide"],"answer":"Pimozide","explanation":"Pimozide is CYP3A4-metabolized, so strong 3A4 inhibitors — macrolides (clarithromycin), azole antifungals, protease inhibitors and grapefruit juice — raise its plasma level and, given its intrinsic QT effect, dangerously prolong the QT interval; these are contraindicated combinations. Droperidol prolongs QT but is short-acting and not defined by this 3A4 contraindication list, pimavanserin is only halved with strong 3A4 inhibitors rather than contraindicated, and trifluoperazine lacks pimozide's marked QT/3A4 interaction profile. The pimozide-plus-macrolide combination is the classic can't-miss interaction.","meds":["droperidol","pimavanserin","trifluoperazine","pimozide"],"focus":"pimozide = CYP3A4 contraindications (macrolides/azoles/grapefruit) + QT","source":{"name":"Pimozide monograph (CYP3A4 drug interactions; QT)","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"pimozide"}],"mood:0":[{"id":"rev_mood_0_1","stem":"A 60-year-old on a mood stabilizer for bipolar I develops nausea, a coarse tremor, ataxia and confusion two weeks after starting a thiazide for hypertension. Which pillar is renally excreted (not metabolized), has a narrow therapeutic index (0.6–1.2 mmol/L; toxic >1.5), and is followed with a 12-hour trough level?","options":["Valproate","Lithium","Lamotrigine"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium is renally cleared and NOT metabolized, so anything that lowers renal clearance — thiazides, NSAIDs, ACEi/ARBs, dehydration, low sodium — raises the level into the toxic range (>1.5 mmol/L: coarse tremor, ataxia, confusion), and it must be dosed to a 12-h trough (0.6–1.2 mmol/L). Contrast: valproate is hepatically metabolized and monitored at 350–700 µmol/L but is not driven toxic by a thiazide; lamotrigine is glucuronidated and has no routine serum level.","meds":["valproate","lithium","lamotrigine"],"focus":"Which pillar is renally cleared with a narrow index requiring 12-h trough levels","source":{"name":"Lithium carbonate product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"lithium"},{"id":"rev_mood_0_2","stem":"A 26-year-old woman with bipolar I who uses no reliable contraception and may wish to conceive needs a maintenance stabilizer. Which of the pillars is the MOST teratogenic — neural-tube defects and the lowest childhood IQ — and should be avoided here?","options":["Lamotrigine","Lithium","Valproate","Carbamazepine"],"answer":"Valproate","explanation":"Valproate is the most teratogenic mood stabilizer: neural-tube defects (spina bifida), craniofacial/cardiac malformations, and dose-dependent neurodevelopmental harm with the LOWEST childhood IQ and increased autism — avoid in anyone who could become pregnant. Contrast: lamotrigine shows no consistent major teratogenic signal and is often preferred in pregnancy; lithium carries a smaller first-trimester Ebstein-anomaly risk; carbamazepine is teratogenic (NTDs) but overall less severe than valproate.","meds":["lamotrigine","lithium","valproate","carbamazepine"],"focus":"Teratogenicity ranking — valproate is the one to avoid in pregnancy potential","source":{"name":"Valproate (divalproex sodium) product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"valproate"},{"id":"rev_mood_0_3","stem":"Which pillar is first-line for bipolar DEPRESSION and maintenance (but ineffective for acute mania), and requires a deliberately SLOW titration — restarting from scratch after a >5-day gap — to reduce the risk of Stevens–Johnson syndrome?","options":["Lamotrigine","Lithium","Valproate"],"answer":"Lamotrigine","explanation":"Lamotrigine is the bipolar-depression/maintenance agent and does NOT treat acute mania; its slow titration exists specifically to lower SJS/TEN risk, and you must restart from scratch after a >5-day gap. Contrast: lithium and valproate are antimanic (valproate can even be loaded for acute mania), and neither carries lamotrigine's rash-driven titration constraint.","meds":["lamotrigine","lithium","valproate"],"focus":"Lamotrigine is the bipolar-depression agent with SJS-driven slow titration","source":{"name":"Lamotrigine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"lamotrigine"},{"id":"rev_mood_0_4","stem":"A patient stable on lamotrigine needs a second agent for a mixed episode. Adding which drug roughly DOUBLES the lamotrigine level by inhibiting its glucuronidation, forcing you to halve the lamotrigine dose to avoid SJS?","options":["Carbamazepine","Valproate","Lithium"],"answer":"Valproate","explanation":"Valproate inhibits lamotrigine glucuronidation, roughly doubling its level — always halve the lamotrigine dose when co-prescribing, because the elevated level raises SJS/TEN risk. Contrast: carbamazepine does the OPPOSITE (induces glucuronidation and LOWERS lamotrigine, risking loss of effect), and lithium is renally cleared and does not touch lamotrigine metabolism.","meds":["carbamazepine","valproate","lithium"],"focus":"Valproate doubles lamotrigine (halve the dose) vs carbamazepine which lowers it","source":{"name":"Lamotrigine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"valproate"},{"id":"rev_mood_0_5","stem":"Of the three pillars, which does NOT require routine serum-level monitoring, in contrast to the two that are dosed to a target trough concentration?","options":["Lithium","Valproate","Lamotrigine"],"answer":"Lamotrigine","explanation":"Lamotrigine has no routine serum level — it is titrated clinically while watching for rash — whereas lithium (0.6–1.2 mmol/L) and valproate (350–700 µmol/L) are dosed to trough targets. The one TDM caveat for lamotrigine is pregnancy, when levels fall markedly and are tracked so the dose can be raised antenatally and reduced postpartum.","meds":["lithium","valproate","lamotrigine"],"focus":"Which pillar needs no routine level — the TDM difference among the three","source":{"name":"Lamotrigine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"lamotrigine"},{"id":"rev_mood_0_6","stem":"Which pillar is the gold-standard mood stabilizer and the ONLY psychotropic with robust evidence for reducing suicide?","options":["Lithium","Valproate","Lamotrigine","Carbamazepine"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium is the reference mood stabilizer and uniquely reduces suicide risk — a benefit that helps justify tolerating its narrow index and monitoring burden. Contrast: valproate and carbamazepine are antimanic anticonvulsants without demonstrated anti-suicide evidence, and lamotrigine covers bipolar depression/maintenance — none share lithium's suicide-reduction data.","meds":["lithium","valproate","lamotrigine","carbamazepine"],"focus":"Lithium's unique anti-suicide evidence distinguishes it from the anticonvulsant pillars","source":{"name":"Lithium carbonate product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"lithium"}],"mood:1":[{"id":"rev_mood_1_1","stem":"Two to four weeks after this anticonvulsant mood stabilizer was titrated to a therapeutic level, the trough has fallen and symptoms return. Which agent AUTOINDUCES its own metabolism, so the level drops over the first weeks and must be rechecked and re-titrated at ~1 month?","options":["Oxcarbazepine","Carbamazepine","Valproate","Lamotrigine"],"answer":"Carbamazepine","explanation":"Carbamazepine induces the CYP3A4 that metabolizes it (autoinduction), so its level falls over the first 2–4 weeks — recheck and re-titrate at ~1 month (target 17–51 µmol/L / 4–12 µg/mL). Contrast: oxcarbazepine has much less autoinduction; valproate does not autoinduce (rather, inducers lower it); lamotrigine has no routine level to fall.","meds":["oxcarbazepine","carbamazepine","valproate","lamotrigine"],"focus":"Carbamazepine autoinduction — recheck the level at ~1 month","source":{"name":"Carbamazepine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"carbamazepine"},{"id":"rev_mood_1_2","stem":"Between these two sodium-channel blockers, in which is clinically significant HYPONATREMIA more common — warranting sodium checks early and in the elderly or diuretic users?","options":["Carbamazepine","Oxcarbazepine"],"answer":"Oxcarbazepine","explanation":"Hyponatremia/SIADH is MORE frequent with oxcarbazepine than with carbamazepine — monitor sodium especially in the first 3 months and in older or diuretic-treated patients (additive with SSRIs and diuretics). Contrast: carbamazepine also causes hyponatremia but less often, and instead carries the heavier hematologic (agranulocytosis/aplastic anemia) monitoring burden.","meds":["carbamazepine","oxcarbazepine"],"focus":"Hyponatremia is more common with oxcarbazepine than carbamazepine","source":{"name":"Oxcarbazepine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"oxcarbazepine"},{"id":"rev_mood_1_3","stem":"Which agent requires HLA-B*1502 screening in patients of Han Chinese / Southeast-Asian ancestry before starting (SJS/TEN risk), can cause agranulocytosis and aplastic anemia, and is a potent 3A4 inducer that causes oral-contraceptive failure?","options":["Lamotrigine","Oxcarbazepine","Carbamazepine"],"answer":"Carbamazepine","explanation":"Carbamazepine carries the HLA-B*1502 SJS/TEN association (screen before starting in at-risk ancestry), marrow suppression (agranulocytosis/aplastic anemia) requiring periodic CBC, and potent 3A4 induction that lowers OCP levels to the point of contraceptive failure (use a non-hormonal method). Contrast: oxcarbazepine shares some HLA-B*1502 cross-risk and weaker induction but far less marrow monitoring; lamotrigine's serious rash is not HLA-B*1502-linked and it does not suppress marrow.","meds":["lamotrigine","oxcarbazepine","carbamazepine"],"focus":"Carbamazepine: HLA-B*1502 screening + agranulocytosis + potent 3A4 inducer (OCP failure)","source":{"name":"Carbamazepine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"carbamazepine"},{"id":"rev_mood_1_4","stem":"Which agent is the keto-analog prodrug (rapidly reduced to the 10-monohydroxy derivative) that lacks the active epoxide — giving better tolerability and much less marrow monitoring, but weaker, off-label evidence as a mood stabilizer?","options":["Oxcarbazepine","Carbamazepine"],"answer":"Oxcarbazepine","explanation":"Oxcarbazepine is the keto-analog of carbamazepine; without the active epoxide it is better tolerated and needs far less hematologic monitoring and re-titration, but its mood-stabilizer evidence is weaker and off-label (not first-line). Contrast: carbamazepine has the stronger antimanic evidence but the epoxide-related toxicity, autoinduction, and CBC-monitoring burden.","meds":["oxcarbazepine","carbamazepine"],"focus":"Oxcarbazepine keto-analog — fewer labs but weaker mood-stabilizer evidence","source":{"name":"Oxcarbazepine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"oxcarbazepine"}],"mood:2":[{"id":"rev_mood_2_1","stem":"Which adjunctive agent causes weight LOSS, cognitive/word-finding slowing (\"dopamax\"), paresthesia, non-anion-gap metabolic acidosis, calcium-phosphate kidney stones, and (idiosyncratically) acute angle-closure glaucoma — all traceable to carbonic-anhydrase inhibition?","options":["Gabapentin","Pregabalin","Topiramate"],"answer":"Topiramate","explanation":"Topiramate's carbonic-anhydrase inhibition ties together the cluster of paresthesia, metabolic acidosis (check bicarbonate), calcium-phosphate stones, and angle-closure glaucoma, and it is the weight-LOSS anticonvulsant with \"dopamax\" cognitive dulling. Contrast: gabapentin and pregabalin are α2δ calcium-channel ligands that cause weight GAIN and peripheral edema, not this metabolic/stone/acidosis cluster.","meds":["gabapentin","pregabalin","topiramate"],"focus":"Topiramate's carbonic-anhydrase cluster + weight loss vs the α2δ pair's weight gain","source":{"name":"Topiramate product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"topiramate"},{"id":"rev_mood_2_2","stem":"Which α2δ calcium-channel ligand has genuine anti-anxiety efficacy with a GAD indication (Europe) and a faster onset than SSRIs, is more potent, and has predictable LINEAR kinetics — though it is an anxiolytic, not a bipolar mood stabilizer?","options":["Pregabalin","Gabapentin","Topiramate"],"answer":"Pregabalin","explanation":"Pregabalin binds the α2δ subunit with linear, reliable absorption and greater potency, and carries a European GAD indication with faster anxiolysis than SSRIs — but it is an anxiolytic, NOT a mood stabilizer, and can be misused. Contrast: gabapentin shares the mechanism but has saturable/nonlinear absorption and no formal anxiety indication; topiramate works by a different (carbonic-anhydrase/AMPA/GABA-A/sodium) mechanism.","meds":["pregabalin","gabapentin","topiramate"],"focus":"Pregabalin — more potent, linear kinetics, GAD anxiolytic (not a mood stabilizer)","source":{"name":"Pregabalin product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"pregabalin"},{"id":"rev_mood_2_3","stem":"Which adjunct is renally excreted with NO CYP metabolism (a clean interaction profile) yet has saturable, nonlinear absorption, has negative bipolar RCTs (used for anxiety/sleep/pain, not as a primary mood stabilizer), and carries recognized misuse potential?","options":["Topiramate","Pregabalin","Gabapentin"],"answer":"Gabapentin","explanation":"Gabapentin is renally cleared with no CYP involvement — clean when polypharmacy/CYP issues matter — but has saturable absorption and no efficacy as a bipolar mood stabilizer (negative RCTs); it is adjunctive and can be misused (respiratory depression with opioids). Contrast: pregabalin is its more potent, linear-kinetics sibling; topiramate is also CYP-independent but has active anticonvulsant/metabolic effects and is used for weight/migraine.","meds":["topiramate","pregabalin","gabapentin"],"focus":"Gabapentin — renal/clean, nonlinear absorption, not a primary mood stabilizer","source":{"name":"Gabapentin product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"gabapentin"},{"id":"rev_mood_2_4","stem":"Both α2δ ligands can be misused, but which one has NONLINEAR (saturable) absorption — bioavailability falling as the dose rises — in contrast to its more potent, linear-kinetics sibling?","options":["Pregabalin","Gabapentin"],"answer":"Gabapentin","explanation":"Gabapentin's absorption is saturable, so bioavailability drops at higher doses and its dose–level relationship is unpredictable. Contrast: pregabalin has linear kinetics and greater potency, giving more reliable dosing — the key pharmacokinetic difference between the two α2δ ligands despite their shared mechanism.","meds":["pregabalin","gabapentin"],"focus":"Gabapentin nonlinear/saturable vs pregabalin linear kinetics","source":{"name":"Gabapentin product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"gabapentin"},{"id":"rev_mood_2_5","stem":"Which adjunct is a teratogen causing oral clefts (cleft lip/palate) and reduced fetal growth, and also lowers oral-contraceptive efficacy at higher doses — so reliable contraception must be counselled?","options":["Gabapentin","Topiramate","Pregabalin"],"answer":"Topiramate","explanation":"Topiramate causes oral clefts and reduced fetal growth and lowers OCP efficacy (>200 mg/day), so counsel on reliable contraception. Contrast: gabapentin and pregabalin have limited pregnancy data (pregabalin carries a possible-harm signal — avoid if possible), but neither is the classic oral-cleft / OCP-interaction teratogen of this row.","meds":["gabapentin","topiramate","pregabalin"],"focus":"Topiramate — oral clefts + reduced OCP efficacy (contraception counselling)","source":{"name":"Topiramate product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"topiramate"}],"anxiolytics:0":[{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_0_1","stem":"A patient with decompensated cirrhosis needs a benzodiazepine for acute anxiety. Which agent is safest here because it is cleared by glucuronidation with NO oxidative CYP step, so its clearance is largely preserved in liver disease?","options":["Lorazepam","Clonazepam","Zopiclone"],"answer":"Lorazepam","explanation":"Lorazepam is a LOT benzo (Lorazepam, Oxazepam, Temazepam) conjugated by UGT glucuronidation with no CYP oxidation, so it is preferred in hepatic impairment. Clonazepam depends on hepatic CYP3A4/nitro-reduction and accumulates when the liver fails; zopiclone is a Z-drug also cleared by CYP3A4.","meds":["lorazepam","clonazepam","zopiclone"],"focus":"LOT benzo (glucuronidation) preferred in hepatic impairment","source":{"name":"Lorazepam / clonazepam / zopiclone monographs — metabolism","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"lorazepam"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_0_2","stem":"Which of these has the LONGEST half-life, making it a long-acting benzodiazepine suited to sustained daytime anxiolysis rather than PRN use?","options":["Zopiclone","Lorazepam","Clonazepam"],"answer":"Clonazepam","explanation":"Clonazepam is long-acting (~18–50 h), giving smooth all-day coverage. Lorazepam is short-to-intermediate (~10–20 h), and zopiclone is very short (~5 h), timed for sleep onset, not daytime anxiolysis.","meds":["zopiclone","lorazepam","clonazepam"],"focus":"half-life / duration: long-acting vs short-acting","source":{"name":"Clonazepam / lorazepam / zopiclone monographs — half-life","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"clonazepam"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_0_3","stem":"For sleep-onset insomnia you want a hypnotic that is NOT a benzodiazepine and (unlike the benzos in this row) is not a controlled/Targeted Substance in Canada. Which fits?","options":["Lorazepam","Zopiclone","Clonazepam"],"answer":"Zopiclone","explanation":"Zopiclone is a non-benzodiazepine cyclopyrrolone (Z-drug) acting at the GABA-A benzodiazepine site but marketed for sleep onset; in Canada it is prescription-only, not a Targeted Substance. Lorazepam and clonazepam are benzodiazepines and Targeted Substances.","meds":["lorazepam","zopiclone","clonazepam"],"focus":"Z-drug vs benzodiazepine / controlled status","source":{"name":"Zopiclone monograph; Canada controlled-substance scheduling","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"zopiclone"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_0_4","stem":"Which of these is available parenterally and given IV as a first-line agent for status epilepticus and acute severe agitation because of its rapid IV onset (1–3 min)?","options":["Zopiclone","Clonazepam","Lorazepam"],"answer":"Lorazepam","explanation":"IV lorazepam acts within 1–3 minutes and is a standard benzodiazepine for status epilepticus and acute agitation. Clonazepam is used orally for chronic anxiety/seizure prophylaxis, and zopiclone is an oral hypnotic only.","meds":["zopiclone","clonazepam","lorazepam"],"focus":"route/onset: IV agent for acute use","source":{"name":"Lorazepam monograph — parenteral onset/indications","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"lorazepam"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_0_5","stem":"A patient with a history of benzodiazepine dependence needs help falling asleep. Which of these carries the least benzodiazepine-dependence liability, being a Z-drug that is not scheduled as a Targeted Substance in Canada?","options":["Clonazepam","Zopiclone","Lorazepam"],"answer":"Zopiclone","explanation":"Zopiclone is not a controlled/Targeted Substance in Canada, whereas lorazepam and clonazepam are Targeted Substances with clear dependence potential. (Zopiclone can still be misused, but among this row it carries the lightest formal control status.)","meds":["clonazepam","zopiclone","lorazepam"],"focus":"dependence / controlled status contrast","source":{"name":"Canada controlled-substance scheduling; zopiclone monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"zopiclone"}],"anxiolytics:1":[{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_1_1","stem":"A patient with generalized anxiety and a substance-use history needs a NON-dependence-forming anxiolytic. Which agent is a 5-HT1A partial agonist with no GABA/benzodiazepine activity, dosed on a schedule (not PRN), whose full effect builds over ~2–4 weeks?","options":["Alprazolam","Buspirone","Hydroxyzine","Diazepam"],"answer":"Buspirone","explanation":"Buspirone is a 5-HT1A partial agonist with no dependence liability, but its onset is delayed (1–2 weeks, full effect ~4 weeks), so it is scheduled BID–TID and useless for acute/PRN anxiety. Alprazolam and diazepam are dependence-forming benzos; hydroxyzine is a fast-acting antihistamine.","meds":["alprazolam","buspirone","hydroxyzine","diazepam"],"focus":"buspirone = non-dependence, delayed onset, scheduled not PRN","source":{"name":"Buspirone monograph — mechanism/onset","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"buspirone"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_1_2","stem":"Which anxiolytic works through central H1-antihistamine antagonism (no GABA/benzodiazepine activity), giving anxiolysis within ~30–60 minutes so it can be used PRN without dependence?","options":["Hydroxyzine","Buspirone","Alprazolam","Zolpidem"],"answer":"Hydroxyzine","explanation":"Hydroxyzine is a first-generation (piperazine) H1-antihistamine; its rapid onset lets it be used PRN with no dependence or controlled status. Buspirone (5-HT1A) is delayed and not PRN; alprazolam is a benzo; zolpidem is a Z-drug hypnotic for sleep.","meds":["hydroxyzine","buspirone","alprazolam","zolpidem"],"focus":"hydroxyzine = non-benzo antihistamine, rapid/PRN","source":{"name":"Hydroxyzine monograph — mechanism/onset","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"hydroxyzine"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_1_3","stem":"For sleep-ONSET insomnia you want a hypnotic that binds preferentially the α1 (BZ1) GABA-A subunit — giving mainly a sedative effect with little anxiolytic or myorelaxant action — and has a very short (~2.5–3 h) half-life. Which agent?","options":["Diazepam","Zolpidem","Alprazolam","Buspirone"],"answer":"Zolpidem","explanation":"Zolpidem is an α1-preferential Z-drug hypnotic with a very short half-life, matched to sleep onset with minimal next-day carryover. Diazepam and alprazolam are anxiolytic benzos; buspirone is a non-sedating 5-HT1A anxiolytic.","meds":["diazepam","zolpidem","alprazolam","buspirone"],"focus":"zolpidem = Z-drug hypnotic, α1-selective, very short","source":{"name":"Zolpidem monograph — receptor selectivity/half-life","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"zolpidem"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_1_4","stem":"Which of these is a high-potency, rapid-onset benzodiazepine whose quick anxiolysis makes it the highest-misuse/dependence-liability agent in this row?","options":["Alprazolam","Buspirone","Hydroxyzine","Zolpidem"],"answer":"Alprazolam","explanation":"Alprazolam's high potency plus rapid PO onset (~20–30 min) strongly reinforces misuse and dependence. Buspirone and hydroxyzine are non-dependence-forming, and zolpidem, while controlled, is a hypnotic rather than a high-potency anxiolytic.","meds":["alprazolam","buspirone","hydroxyzine","zolpidem"],"focus":"dependence/misuse liability of high-potency benzo","source":{"name":"Alprazolam monograph — onset/abuse liability","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"alprazolam"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_1_5","stem":"Which benzodiazepine combines a very rapid CNS onset (highly lipophilic) with a LONG effective duration via active metabolites (desmethyldiazepam up to ~200 h), so it accumulates and is favoured for smooth benzodiazepine tapers?","options":["Zolpidem","Alprazolam","Diazepam","Buspirone"],"answer":"Diazepam","explanation":"Diazepam is highly lipophilic (fast onset) but generates long-lived active metabolites (nordiazepam ~200 h), giving self-tapering kinetics useful in withdrawal but risking accumulation in the elderly/hepatically impaired. Alprazolam is short-acting; zolpidem and buspirone are not long-acting benzos.","meds":["zolpidem","alprazolam","diazepam","buspirone"],"focus":"long half-life via active metabolites / accumulation","source":{"name":"Diazepam monograph — half-life/active metabolites","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"diazepam"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_1_6","stem":"A patient asks for something to take at the onset of an acute panic/anxiety episode. Which of these would NOT help acutely because its anxiolytic effect only builds over 1–2 weeks?","options":["Hydroxyzine","Alprazolam","Buspirone","Diazepam"],"answer":"Buspirone","explanation":"Buspirone has a delayed onset (~1–2 weeks, full effect ~4 weeks) and is NOT effective PRN for acute anxiety. Hydroxyzine, alprazolam, and diazepam all act within an hour and can blunt an acute episode.","meds":["hydroxyzine","alprazolam","buspirone","diazepam"],"focus":"onset — buspirone not for acute/PRN use","source":{"name":"Buspirone monograph — delayed onset","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"buspirone"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_1_7","stem":"Two agents in this row avoid dependence entirely. Which one gives anxiolysis within ~30–60 minutes and can therefore be used PRN — unlike the other non-dependence agent, which must be taken on a schedule and takes weeks to work?","options":["Buspirone","Hydroxyzine","Alprazolam","Zolpidem"],"answer":"Hydroxyzine","explanation":"Both hydroxyzine and buspirone lack dependence liability, but hydroxyzine (antihistamine) acts within an hour and works PRN, whereas buspirone (5-HT1A) is scheduled with a multi-week onset. Alprazolam and zolpidem are controlled and dependence-forming.","meds":["buspirone","hydroxyzine","alprazolam","zolpidem"],"focus":"non-dependence agents: rapid/PRN (hydroxyzine) vs scheduled/delayed (buspirone)","source":{"name":"Hydroxyzine vs buspirone monographs — onset","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"hydroxyzine"}],"anxiolytics:2":[{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_2_1","stem":"An anxious patient with significant liver disease needs a benzodiazepine. Which agent is cleared solely by glucuronidation (no oxidative CYP step) and has slow, least-abuse-reinforcing kinetics, making it a preferred choice in hepatic impairment?","options":["Bromazepam","Oxazepam","Chlordiazepoxide","Temazepam"],"answer":"Oxazepam","explanation":"Oxazepam is a LOT benzo conjugated by UGT with no CYP oxidation, so it is liver-safe; its slow onset also makes it the least abuse-reinforcing benzo. Bromazepam and chlordiazepoxide undergo hepatic oxidation (chlordiazepoxide to long-lived active metabolites). Temazepam is also a LOT benzo but is marketed as a hypnotic.","meds":["bromazepam","oxazepam","chlordiazepoxide","temazepam"],"focus":"LOT benzo (glucuronidation) for hepatic impairment","source":{"name":"Oxazepam monograph — metabolism/onset","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"oxazepam"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_2_2","stem":"Which of these is a benzodiazepine marketed specifically as a HYPNOTIC for sleep, yet (like oxazepam) is metabolized only by glucuronidation with no CYP oxidation, so it is comparatively liver-safe?","options":["Bromazepam","Chlordiazepoxide","Temazepam","Oxazepam"],"answer":"Temazepam","explanation":"Temazepam is a LOT benzo (glucuronidation only) positioned as a hypnotic, with an intermediate half-life (~8–15 h) that limits next-day hangover versus long-acting agents. Oxazepam is a LOT benzo too but is used for anxiety; bromazepam and chlordiazepoxide are oxidatively metabolized anxiety agents.","meds":["bromazepam","chlordiazepoxide","temazepam","oxazepam"],"focus":"hypnotic LOT benzo (temazepam vs anxiety agents)","source":{"name":"Temazepam monograph — indication/metabolism","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"temazepam"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_2_3","stem":"Which of these is the classic LONG-acting benzodiazepine (with long-lived active metabolites) traditionally used for managing alcohol withdrawal?","options":["Oxazepam","Temazepam","Chlordiazepoxide","Bromazepam"],"answer":"Chlordiazepoxide","explanation":"Chlordiazepoxide generates active metabolites (including desmethyldiazepam) that give long-acting, self-tapering coverage ideal for alcohol withdrawal. Oxazepam and temazepam are short/intermediate LOT benzos (oxazepam is used for withdrawal when the liver is impaired); bromazepam is an intermediate anxiety agent.","meds":["oxazepam","temazepam","chlordiazepoxide","bromazepam"],"focus":"long-acting active metabolites / alcohol withdrawal","source":{"name":"Chlordiazepoxide monograph — metabolites/indication","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"chlordiazepoxide"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_2_4","stem":"Which is an intermediate-acting benzodiazepine marketed for generalized anxiety that is cleared by hepatic CYP oxidation — unlike the glucuronidation-only LOT benzos in this row?","options":["Oxazepam","Bromazepam","Temazepam","Chlordiazepoxide"],"answer":"Bromazepam","explanation":"Bromazepam (~10–20 h) is an oxidatively metabolized anxiety benzodiazepine. Oxazepam and temazepam are conjugated only (LOT, liver-safe); chlordiazepoxide is oxidatively metabolized but is long-acting via active metabolites and used for withdrawal, not primarily GAD.","meds":["oxazepam","bromazepam","temazepam","chlordiazepoxide"],"focus":"oxidative vs conjugated (glucuronidation) metabolism","source":{"name":"Bromazepam monograph — half-life/metabolism","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"bromazepam"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_2_5","stem":"For insomnia with both sleep-onset AND sleep-maintenance problems, which agent works by competitively blocking orexin (OX1R/OX2R) wake-promoting signalling, with no GABA/benzodiazepine activity and no controlled-substance status?","options":["Lemborexant","Daridorexant","Melatonin","Temazepam"],"answer":"Lemborexant","explanation":"Lemborexant is a dual orexin receptor antagonist (DORA) that promotes both sleep onset and maintenance without GABA-A activity. Daridorexant is also a DORA but with a shorter half-life; melatonin is a melatonergic agonist; temazepam is a GABAergic benzodiazepine.","meds":["lemborexant","daridorexant","melatonin","temazepam"],"focus":"orexin-antagonist mechanism (DORA)","source":{"name":"Lemborexant monograph — mechanism","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"lemborexant"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_2_6","stem":"Between the two dual orexin receptor antagonists, which has the SHORTER half-life (~8 h) — deliberately designed to minimize next-day residual sedation?","options":["Lemborexant","Daridorexant","Temazepam","Melatonin"],"answer":"Daridorexant","explanation":"Daridorexant's ~8 h half-life is shorter than lemborexant's ~17–19 h, reducing morning grogginess. Both are DORAs with no GABA activity; temazepam and melatonin work by entirely different mechanisms.","meds":["lemborexant","daridorexant","temazepam","melatonin"],"focus":"half-life among DORAs / next-day residual","source":{"name":"Daridorexant vs lemborexant monographs — half-life","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"daridorexant"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_2_7","stem":"Which sleep aid is an MT1/MT2 melatonin-receptor agonist (an endogenous pineal hormone) that only weakly promotes sleep onset and works through the circadian system rather than GABA?","options":["Lemborexant","Daridorexant","Melatonin","Temazepam"],"answer":"Melatonin","explanation":"Melatonin acts at MT1 (sleep onset) and MT2 (circadian phase-shift) receptors, a melatonergic mechanism distinct from the orexin antagonists (lemborexant, daridorexant) and the GABAergic temazepam.","meds":["lemborexant","daridorexant","melatonin","temazepam"],"focus":"melatonergic (MT1/MT2) mechanism vs orexin/GABA","source":{"name":"Melatonin monograph — receptor mechanism","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"melatonin"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_2_8","stem":"A shift worker wants to phase-shift their body clock. Which agent's effect on sleep depends chiefly on the TIMING of the dose relative to the circadian rhythm rather than on a sedative dose effect?","options":["Temazepam","Lemborexant","Daridorexant","Melatonin"],"answer":"Melatonin","explanation":"Melatonin's circadian phase-shifting is timing-dependent (via MT2), so administration time relative to the body clock matters more than dose. The DORAs (lemborexant, daridorexant) and the benzodiazepine temazepam act pharmacologically at any suitable bedtime without a circadian-timing requirement.","meds":["temazepam","lemborexant","daridorexant","melatonin"],"focus":"circadian timing (melatonin) vs dose-driven sedation","source":{"name":"Melatonin monograph — circadian timing","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"melatonin"}],"anxiolytics:3":[{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_3_1","stem":"For procedural sedation you need an ultra-short-acting benzodiazepine with very fast parenteral onset (IV 1–3 min, also IM/intranasal). Which agent is the standard choice?","options":["Triazolam","Midazolam","Nitrazepam","Phenobarbital"],"answer":"Midazolam","explanation":"Midazolam is water-soluble at low pH but lipophilic at physiologic pH, giving rapid CNS entry and a brief (~1.5–3 h) effect ideal for procedural sedation. Triazolam is an oral ultra-short hypnotic; nitrazepam is a long-acting hypnotic; phenobarbital is a long-acting barbiturate.","meds":["triazolam","midazolam","nitrazepam","phenobarbital"],"focus":"procedural sedation: ultra-short parenteral benzo","source":{"name":"Midazolam monograph — onset/duration/routes","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"midazolam"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_3_2","stem":"Which ultra-short-acting benzodiazepine HYPNOTIC undergoes extensive CYP3A4 first-pass metabolism, so strong 3A4 inhibitors (e.g., azole antifungals, macrolides) dramatically raise its levels and are labelled contraindications?","options":["Triazolam","Midazolam","Flurazepam","Nitrazepam"],"answer":"Triazolam","explanation":"Triazolam is an oral ultra-short hypnotic with heavy CYP3A4 first-pass metabolism and numerous labelled 3A4-inhibitor contraindications. Midazolam is also 3A4-dependent but is a parenteral procedural agent; flurazepam and nitrazepam are long-acting hypnotics.","meds":["triazolam","midazolam","flurazepam","nitrazepam"],"focus":"CYP3A4 interactions / ultra-short hypnotic","source":{"name":"Triazolam monograph — metabolism/interactions","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"triazolam"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_3_3","stem":"Which agent is a barbiturate that increases the DURATION of GABA-A chloride-channel opening (and at high concentrations opens the channel directly, independent of GABA) — giving it NO ceiling effect and a high risk of fatal respiratory depression in overdose?","options":["Midazolam","Phenobarbital","Clobazam","Clorazepate"],"answer":"Phenobarbital","explanation":"Phenobarbital is a barbiturate: it prolongs Cl- channel-opening DURATION (benzodiazepines instead raise opening FREQUENCY) and directly opens the channel at high doses, so there is no ceiling and overdose causes profound respiratory depression. It is also a potent enzyme inducer and a Controlled Drug. The others are benzodiazepines with a ceiling effect and lower overdose lethality.","meds":["midazolam","phenobarbital","clobazam","clorazepate"],"focus":"barbiturate mechanism (duration, no ceiling) vs benzodiazepine","source":{"name":"Phenobarbital monograph — mechanism/overdose","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"phenobarbital"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_3_4","stem":"Which sleep aid is a selective melatonin MT1/MT2 receptor agonist with no GABA/benzodiazepine activity and no controlled-substance status, useful for sleep-ONSET insomnia?","options":["Triazolam","Nitrazepam","Phenobarbital","Ramelteon"],"answer":"Ramelteon","explanation":"Ramelteon is a melatonergic MT1/MT2 agonist that reduces sleep latency without GABA activity or dependence liability. Triazolam and nitrazepam are benzodiazepines (Targeted Substances); phenobarbital is a Controlled Drug barbiturate.","meds":["triazolam","nitrazepam","phenobarbital","ramelteon"],"focus":"melatonergic, non-controlled hypnotic vs GABAergic agents","source":{"name":"Ramelteon monograph — mechanism/scheduling","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"ramelteon"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_3_5","stem":"Which is a 1,5-benzodiazepine whose structure gives relatively MORE anticonvulsant/anxiolytic effect with comparatively LESS sedation, used as an adjunct for seizures (e.g., Lennox-Gastaut)?","options":["Clorazepate","Nitrazepam","Clobazam","Flurazepam"],"answer":"Clobazam","explanation":"Clobazam is a 1,5-benzodiazepine (versus the classic 1,4 structure), giving more anticonvulsant/anxiolytic action with less sedation, and is used as a seizure adjunct. Clorazepate is a long-acting prodrug; nitrazepam and flurazepam are sedating long-acting hypnotics.","meds":["clorazepate","nitrazepam","clobazam","flurazepam"],"focus":"1,5-benzodiazepine: anticonvulsant, less sedation","source":{"name":"Clobazam monograph — structure/indication","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"clobazam"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_3_6","stem":"Which agent is a benzodiazepine PRODRUG that is decarboxylated in the acidic stomach to desmethyldiazepam (nordiazepam), giving it long-acting kinetics?","options":["Clobazam","Clorazepate","Flurazepam","Triazolam"],"answer":"Clorazepate","explanation":"Clorazepate is converted pre-systemically in the stomach to nordiazepam (half-life up to ~100–200 h), so it behaves as a long-acting agent. Clobazam is a 1,5-benzodiazepine, flurazepam is a hypnotic with its own active metabolite, and triazolam is ultra-short-acting.","meds":["clobazam","clorazepate","flurazepam","triazolam"],"focus":"prodrug → long-acting nordiazepam","source":{"name":"Clorazepate monograph — prodrug/metabolism","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"clorazepate"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_3_7","stem":"Which hypnotic has a short-lived PARENT drug but owes its prolonged action (and next-day accumulation risk, especially in the elderly) to an ACTIVE metabolite with a half-life up to ~250 hours?","options":["Triazolam","Midazolam","Flurazepam","Nitrazepam"],"answer":"Flurazepam","explanation":"Flurazepam's parent is short-acting, but its metabolite N-desalkylflurazepam (~40–250 h) accumulates and causes next-day sedation. Triazolam and midazolam are ultra-short with no such metabolite; nitrazepam is long-acting through its own long parent half-life, not an active metabolite.","meds":["triazolam","midazolam","flurazepam","nitrazepam"],"focus":"long duration via long-lived active metabolite / accumulation","source":{"name":"Flurazepam monograph — active metabolite half-life","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"flurazepam"},{"id":"rev_anxiolytics_3_8","stem":"Which is a LONG-acting benzodiazepine hypnotic (parent half-life ~16–40 h) that commonly causes next-day residual sedation, in contrast to the ultra-short agents used for procedures?","options":["Triazolam","Midazolam","Nitrazepam","Ramelteon"],"answer":"Nitrazepam","explanation":"Nitrazepam's own long parent half-life (~16–40 h) produces hangover/next-day residual sedation. Triazolam and midazolam are ultra-short-acting; ramelteon is a short-acting melatonergic agent with no GABA activity.","meds":["triazolam","midazolam","nitrazepam","ramelteon"],"focus":"long parent half-life / next-day residual sedation","source":{"name":"Nitrazepam monograph — half-life","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"nitrazepam"}],"adhd:0":[{"id":"rev_adhd_0_1","stem":"You are choosing a first-line stimulant and want to teach the trainee the core mechanistic split. Which of these two first-line agents works purely by BLOCKING the dopamine/norepinephrine transporters (DAT/NET) to raise synaptic catecholamines, WITHOUT driving vesicular release of dopamine?","options":["Methylphenidate","Lisdexamfetamine"],"answer":"Methylphenidate","explanation":"Methylphenidate is a pure reuptake blocker (DAT/NET) — it does not trigger vesicular release. Lisdexamfetamine is a prodrug of dextroamphetamine, and amphetamines primarily RELEASE dopamine/norepinephrine (reversing the transporters/VMAT2) in addition to blocking reuptake. That releaser-vs-blocker distinction is the fundamental way these two first-line stimulant families differ.","meds":["methylphenidate","lisdexamfetamine"],"focus":"mechanism: methylphenidate = reuptake blocker vs lisdexamfetamine/amphetamine = releaser","source":{"name":"Methylphenidate product monograph — reuptake-blockade mechanism","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"methylphenidate"},{"id":"rev_adhd_0_2","stem":"A university student with ADHD lives in a shared dorm and previously had a stimulant crushed and snorted by a roommate. You want the first-line agent least able to produce a rapid 'high' if insufflated or injected. Which one is an inactive prodrug that must be enzymatically hydrolyzed in the bloodstream before it becomes active?","options":["Methylphenidate","Lisdexamfetamine"],"answer":"Lisdexamfetamine","explanation":"Lisdexamfetamine is d-amphetamine covalently bound to L-lysine — inactive until red-blood-cell peptidases hydrolyze it to active dextroamphetamine. Because conversion is rate-limited and happens in the blood, snorting or injecting it does not generate a fast euphoric surge, giving it the lowest misuse liability of the stimulants. Methylphenidate is immediately active and can be insufflated for effect. Both are Controlled Drugs in Canada, but only the prodrug specifically defeats the snort/inject route.","meds":["methylphenidate","lisdexamfetamine"],"focus":"prodrug / low diversion liability of lisdexamfetamine","source":{"name":"Lisdexamfetamine product monograph — prodrug activation & misuse","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"lisdexamfetamine"},{"id":"rev_adhd_0_3","stem":"You are adding a stimulant for a patient already on several CYP-metabolized psychotropics and want to minimize pharmacokinetic drug interactions. Which first-line stimulant is cleared mainly by carboxylesterase (CES1) rather than CYP enzymes, giving it notably few PK interactions?","options":["Lisdexamfetamine","Methylphenidate"],"answer":"Methylphenidate","explanation":"Methylphenidate is metabolized by carboxylesterase (CES1), not the CYP system, so it has far fewer pharmacokinetic interactions than most psychotropics — useful in polypharmacy. Lisdexamfetamine's conversion depends on RBC peptidase hydrolysis and, like other amphetamines, its exposure is sensitive to urine pH rather than being a 'clean' CES1 story. This makes methylphenidate the more interaction-sparing pick here.","meds":["lisdexamfetamine","methylphenidate"],"focus":"methylphenidate CES1 metabolism → few PK interactions","source":{"name":"Methylphenidate product monograph — CES1 metabolism & interactions","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"methylphenidate"}],"adhd:1":[{"id":"rev_adhd_1_1","stem":"A patient on a pure single-enantiomer amphetamine is switched to a preparation with more prominent peripheral cardiovascular (noradrenergic) effect at a comparable dose. Which of these 'other stimulant' options is a 3:1 dextro-to-levoamphetamine blend, whose levo-isomer contributes relatively more peripheral noradrenergic effect?","options":["Dextroamphetamine","Amphetamine mixed salts"],"answer":"Amphetamine mixed salts","explanation":"Mixed amphetamine salts are roughly a 3:1 d:l-amphetamine blend; the l-isomer adds relatively more peripheral noradrenergic (cardiovascular) effect than pure dextroamphetamine. Dextroamphetamine is the single d-enantiomer without that added levo component. Both are releasers and share amphetamine's misuse potential and MAOI contraindication — the practical difference here is the l-isomer's cardiovascular contribution.","meds":["dextroamphetamine","amphetamine_salts"],"focus":"mixed salts = 3:1 d:l blend, l-isomer adds peripheral CV effect","source":{"name":"Mixed amphetamine salts product monograph — enantiomer composition","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"amphetamine_salts"},{"id":"rev_adhd_1_2","stem":"You want to prescribe the amphetamine preparation that contains ONLY the dextro-enantiomer, without any added levoamphetamine. Which of these 'other stimulant' options fits?","options":["Dextroamphetamine","Amphetamine mixed salts"],"answer":"Dextroamphetamine","explanation":"Dextroamphetamine is the pure single d-enantiomer. Mixed amphetamine salts deliberately combine d- and l-amphetamine in about a 3:1 ratio, adding the levo component (and its greater peripheral noradrenergic effect). Both act primarily by releasing dopamine/norepinephrine and blocking reuptake; the distinction is enantiomer content, not mechanism class.","meds":["dextroamphetamine","amphetamine_salts"],"focus":"dextroamphetamine = single d-enantiomer (coverage / contrast with mixed salts)","source":{"name":"Dextroamphetamine product monograph — single-enantiomer composition","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"dextroamphetamine"},{"id":"rev_adhd_1_3","stem":"To reinforce the amphetamine-vs-methylphenidate contrast: which agent primarily drives presynaptic RELEASE of dopamine and norepinephrine — entering the neuron via DAT/NET and reversing the transporters/VMAT2 — rather than only blocking reuptake?","options":["Methylphenidate","Dextroamphetamine"],"answer":"Dextroamphetamine","explanation":"Dextroamphetamine (like all amphetamines) is a releaser: it enters the presynaptic terminal via DAT/NET and drives dopamine/norepinephrine release by reversing the transporters and VMAT2, and it also blocks reuptake. Methylphenidate is a pure reuptake blocker that does NOT release transmitter. This releaser-vs-blocker split is the mechanistic anchor separating the amphetamine stimulants from methylphenidate.","meds":["methylphenidate","dextroamphetamine"],"focus":"amphetamine = releaser vs methylphenidate = reuptake blocker","source":{"name":"Dextroamphetamine product monograph — releaser mechanism","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"dextroamphetamine"}],"adhd:2":[{"id":"rev_adhd_2_1","stem":"You need an ADHD agent for a patient where diversion risk and same-day 'boost' are concerns, and the family should expect a gradual, not immediate, benefit. Which non-stimulant is a selective norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor whose meaningful effect builds over about 2–4 weeks and which is NOT a controlled substance?","options":["Atomoxetine","Guanfacine","Clonidine"],"answer":"Atomoxetine","explanation":"Atomoxetine is a selective norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor (NRI). It raises prefrontal NE/DA without a striatal dopamine surge, so it has essentially no misuse potential (not controlled) but takes about 2–4 weeks for full effect — unlike the same-day stimulants. Guanfacine and clonidine are α2-adrenergic agonists (also non-controlled), a different mechanism; the NRI-with-delayed-onset description points specifically to atomoxetine.","meds":["atomoxetine","guanfacine","clonidine"],"focus":"atomoxetine = non-stimulant NRI, delayed 2–4 wk onset, not controlled","source":{"name":"Atomoxetine product monograph — mechanism & delayed onset","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"atomoxetine"},{"id":"rev_adhd_2_2","stem":"You want an α2-adrenergic agent for ADHD but daytime sedation and hypotension must be minimized, and you specifically want the more α2A-selective agent that carries its own ADHD (extended-release) indication and an approved stimulant-adjunct role. Which do you choose?","options":["Clonidine","Guanfacine","Atomoxetine"],"answer":"Guanfacine","explanation":"Guanfacine is a selective α2A-agonist — more α2A-selective than clonidine — so it is relatively less sedating and hypotensive for a given effect, and it is the α2 agonist with a specific ADHD (XR) indication plus an approved stimulant-adjunct role. Clonidine is less α2A-selective and markedly more sedating. Atomoxetine is an NRI, not an α2 agonist. Note guanfacine is CYP3A4-metabolized and must be tapered (rebound hypertension).","meds":["clonidine","guanfacine","atomoxetine"],"focus":"guanfacine = α2A-selective, less sedating, ADHD-XR indication + adjunct role","source":{"name":"Guanfacine XR product monograph — α2A selectivity & indication","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"guanfacine"},{"id":"rev_adhd_2_3","stem":"A child with ADHD also has motor tics and prominent sleep-onset insomnia, and you want the α2 agonist that is more sedating (useful dosed at bedtime) and favoured in this tic/sleep scenario. Which agent — also the classic dangerous pediatric overdose that mimics opioid toxicity — fits best?","options":["Atomoxetine","Guanfacine","Clonidine"],"answer":"Clonidine","explanation":"Clonidine is less α2A-selective, shorter-acting and MORE sedating than guanfacine, so it is favoured for sleep-onset insomnia and tics and is often dosed at bedtime. Its pediatric overdose is a classic potentially lethal ingestion — CNS/respiratory depression, bradycardia and miosis mimicking opioid toxicity — and rebound hypertension on abrupt withdrawal is more marked than with guanfacine, so it must be tapered. Guanfacine is the less-sedating α2A-selective agent; atomoxetine is an NRI.","meds":["atomoxetine","guanfacine","clonidine"],"focus":"clonidine = more sedating, tics/sleep-onset, lethal pediatric overdose","source":{"name":"Clonidine product monograph — sedation, tics/insomnia use & overdose","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"clonidine"},{"id":"rev_adhd_2_4","stem":"Between the two α2A-adrenergic agonists on this row, a family needs the option LEAST likely to cause daytime somnolence and hypotension for a comparable ADHD effect. Which do you pick?","options":["Clonidine","Guanfacine"],"answer":"Guanfacine","explanation":"Guanfacine is more α2A-selective than clonidine, so it produces relatively less sedation and hypotension for a given ADHD effect — the better fit when daytime alertness must be preserved. Clonidine is less selective and markedly more sedating (which is exactly why it is favoured at bedtime for sleep-onset insomnia). Both still cause hypotension/bradycardia and both require tapering to avoid rebound hypertension.","meds":["clonidine","guanfacine"],"focus":"guanfacine (α2A-selective, less sedating) vs clonidine (more sedating)","source":{"name":"CADDRA/CANMAT ADHD guidance — α2 agonist selection","origin":"canmat"},"answerId":"guanfacine"},{"id":"rev_adhd_2_5","stem":"One of these non-stimulants carries a warning for rare but potentially severe hepatotoxicity — you would stop it for jaundice or markedly elevated LFTs and not rechallenge — and it also carries a suicidal-ideation caution in children/adolescents. Which agent is it?","options":["Guanfacine","Clonidine","Atomoxetine"],"answer":"Atomoxetine","explanation":"Atomoxetine carries warnings for rare, potentially severe hepatotoxicity (discontinue for jaundice or markedly elevated LFTs and do not rechallenge) and for suicidal ideation in children/adolescents, warranting close early monitoring. Guanfacine and clonidine are α2 agonists whose principal cautions are hypotension, bradycardia, sedation and rebound hypertension on abrupt withdrawal — not hepatotoxicity. This safety profile distinguishes the NRI from the α2 agonists.","meds":["guanfacine","clonidine","atomoxetine"],"focus":"atomoxetine hepatotoxicity + pediatric suicidality warning (vs α2 agonists)","source":{"name":"Atomoxetine product monograph — hepatotoxicity & suicidality warnings","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"atomoxetine"}],"substance:0":[{"id":"rev_substance_0_1","stem":"On the OAT induction ward you need the agent that is a FULL mu-opioid agonist with no ceiling on respiratory depression, whose dose-dependent QT prolongation warrants a baseline and follow-up ECG. Which do you choose?","options":["Methadone","Buprenorphine/naloxone","Naltrexone","Naloxone"],"answer":"Methadone","explanation":"Methadone is a full mu agonist, so unlike buprenorphine's partial-agonist ceiling there is no plateau on respiratory depression, and it prolongs QT dose-dependently (get an ECG, especially >100 mg). Buprenorphine/naloxone has the safety ceiling and minimal QT effect; naltrexone and naloxone are antagonists, not agonists.","meds":["methadone","buprenorphine_naloxone","naltrexone","naloxone"],"focus":"full-agonist QTc/no-ceiling (methadone) vs partial-agonist ceiling (buprenorphine)","source":{"name":"Methadone product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"methadone"},{"id":"rev_substance_0_2","stem":"A stable patient's take-home OAT contains a second ingredient that is essentially inert when the film is taken sublingually but precipitates withdrawal if the product is dissolved and injected, deterring IV misuse. Which agent is this?","options":["Buprenorphine/naloxone","Methadone","Naltrexone","Naloxone"],"answer":"Buprenorphine/naloxone","explanation":"In buprenorphine/naloxone the naloxone is poorly bioavailable sublingually (inert if used correctly) and only blocks the high / precipitates withdrawal if injected — an abuse-deterrent. The precipitated-withdrawal caution on INDUCTION, by contrast, is driven by buprenorphine's high mu affinity, not the naloxone. Methadone is a single full agonist; naltrexone and naloxone are standalone antagonists.","meds":["buprenorphine_naloxone","methadone","naltrexone","naloxone"],"focus":"combo product: naloxone as abuse-deterrent (inert SL) vs buprenorphine-driven induction risk","source":{"name":"Buprenorphine/naloxone product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"buprenorphine_naloxone"},{"id":"rev_substance_0_3","stem":"EMS reverses an overdose with a SHORT-acting pure opioid antagonist, then you counsel the family to keep watching the patient because it can wear off before a long-acting opioid does. Which agent was used?","options":["Naloxone","Naltrexone","Methadone","Buprenorphine/naloxone"],"answer":"Naloxone","explanation":"Naloxone is the short-acting overdose RESCUE antagonist; because it can wear off before methadone or extended-release opioids clear, re-narcotization is the key risk (re-dose or infuse, always call EMS). Naltrexone is the LONG-acting maintenance antagonist, not a rescue agent; methadone and buprenorphine/naloxone are agonist therapies.","meds":["naloxone","naltrexone","methadone","buprenorphine_naloxone"],"focus":"short-acting rescue antagonist (naloxone) vs long-acting maintenance antagonist (naltrexone)","source":{"name":"Naloxone product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"naloxone"},{"id":"rev_substance_0_4","stem":"Before starting an OUD relapse-prevention agent you insist on roughly 7-10 opioid-free days, and you note it is contraindicated in anyone still receiving opioid ANALGESICS. Skipping the washout would precipitate withdrawal. Which agent demands this?","options":["Naltrexone","Naloxone","Methadone","Buprenorphine/naloxone"],"answer":"Naltrexone","explanation":"Naltrexone is a maintenance antagonist, so the patient must be opioid-free ~7-10 days or you precipitate withdrawal, and it is contraindicated with opioid analgesics / current opioid dependence (plan non-opioid or regional analgesia for surgery). Naloxone is the acute rescue antagonist, not maintenance; methadone and buprenorphine/naloxone are agonists started IN objective withdrawal, not after a washout.","meds":["naltrexone","naloxone","methadone","buprenorphine_naloxone"],"focus":"naltrexone opioid-free interval + opioid-analgesic contraindication","source":{"name":"Naltrexone product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"naltrexone"},{"id":"rev_substance_0_5","stem":"Two of the OUD-core agents are opioid antagonists. One is the emergency reversal drug; the other is a once-monthly-capable maintenance drug that also cuts heavy-drinking days in alcohol use disorder. Which is the MAINTENANCE antagonist?","options":["Naltrexone","Naloxone"],"answer":"Naltrexone","explanation":"Both block mu receptors, but naltrexone is the long-acting oral / IM-depot MAINTENANCE antagonist — dual use for detoxified OUD relapse prevention and for reducing craving/heavy drinking in AUD. Naloxone is the short-acting emergency reversal agent only. Confusing the two matters: giving naltrexone to someone still on opioids precipitates withdrawal.","meds":["naltrexone","naloxone"],"focus":"naltrexone (maintenance, dual AUD/OUD) vs naloxone (acute rescue)","source":{"name":"Naltrexone product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"naltrexone"},{"id":"rev_substance_0_6","stem":"For most patients starting OAT, national (CRISM) guidance favours the agent whose partial-agonist ceiling on respiratory depression makes overdose safer than the full agonist. Which is preferred first-line?","options":["Buprenorphine/naloxone","Methadone","Naltrexone","Naloxone"],"answer":"Buprenorphine/naloxone","explanation":"Buprenorphine/naloxone is first-line OAT for most patients because buprenorphine's partial-agonist ceiling limits respiratory depression, unlike methadone's full-agonist risk (accumulation, delayed overdose in the first 1-2 weeks, QT/torsades). Methadone remains a valid full-agonist option; naltrexone/naloxone are antagonists, not agonist maintenance.","meds":["buprenorphine_naloxone","methadone","naltrexone","naloxone"],"focus":"first-line safety ceiling (buprenorphine/naloxone) vs full-agonist methadone","source":{"name":"CRISM national OUD/OAT guideline","origin":"guideline"},"answerId":"buprenorphine_naloxone"}],"substance:1":[{"id":"rev_substance_1_1","stem":"You want an AUD strategy that works by DETERRENCE: it irreversibly inhibits aldehyde dehydrogenase so any drinking floods the patient with acetaldehyde, causing flushing, throbbing headache and vomiting. Which agent is this?","options":["Disulfiram","Acamprosate","Naltrexone","Varenicline"],"answer":"Disulfiram","explanation":"Disulfiram irreversibly blocks ALDH, so acetaldehyde accumulates and produces the aversive disulfiram-alcohol reaction — a deterrent, not an anti-craving effect. Acamprosate and naltrexone reduce craving without any aversive reaction; varenicline treats nicotine, not alcohol.","meds":["disulfiram","acamprosate","naltrexone","varenicline"],"focus":"aversive ALDH inhibition (disulfiram) vs anti-craving agents","source":{"name":"Disulfiram product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"disulfiram"},{"id":"rev_substance_1_2","stem":"For maintaining abstinence in an already-abstinent patient you pick a non-aversive AUD agent that is renally excreted unchanged (so it must be avoided in severe renal impairment, CrCl <=30) rather than hepatically metabolized. Which agent?","options":["Acamprosate","Disulfiram","Naltrexone","Varenicline"],"answer":"Acamprosate","explanation":"Acamprosate modulates glutamate/GABA to support abstinence, is renally cleared (contraindicated in severe renal impairment, CrCl <=30 mL/min) and non-aversive. It does NOT treat acute withdrawal. Contrast disulfiram (aversive, hepatotoxic) and naltrexone (hepatotoxic, hepatically handled); varenicline is for smoking cessation.","meds":["acamprosate","disulfiram","naltrexone","varenicline"],"focus":"acamprosate renal clearance / non-aversive maintenance","source":{"name":"Acamprosate product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"acamprosate"},{"id":"rev_substance_1_3","stem":"A patient wants to quit SMOKING. You reach for the alpha4-beta2 nicotinic partial agonist — the most effective single pharmacotherapy for cessation — and tell them to start it about a week before their quit date. Which agent?","options":["Varenicline","Acamprosate","Disulfiram","Naltrexone"],"answer":"Varenicline","explanation":"Varenicline is an alpha4-beta2 nicotinic partial agonist: partial stimulation eases craving/withdrawal while blocking nicotine's reward. Start ~1 week before the quit date; nausea and vivid dreams are hallmark effects. Acamprosate and disulfiram/naltrexone target ALCOHOL, not nicotine.","meds":["varenicline","acamprosate","disulfiram","naltrexone"],"focus":"varenicline for nicotine cessation vs alcohol-use-disorder agents","source":{"name":"Varenicline product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"varenicline"},{"id":"rev_substance_1_4","stem":"Which AUD medication is appropriate ONLY for a motivated, insightful, already-abstinent patient who understands that a slip will trigger a punishing physical reaction, and is best taken under supervision — because its whole strategy is deterrence rather than craving reduction?","options":["Disulfiram","Acamprosate","Varenicline","Naltrexone"],"answer":"Disulfiram","explanation":"Disulfiram's aversive mechanism requires a motivated, insightful, abstinent patient (and must never be given without their knowledge or while intoxicated); it is not first-line. Acamprosate and naltrexone are anti-craving agents that do not depend on fear of a reaction; varenicline is for smoking.","meds":["disulfiram","acamprosate","varenicline","naltrexone"],"focus":"aversive-therapy patient selection (disulfiram) vs anti-craving agents","source":{"name":"Disulfiram product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"disulfiram"},{"id":"rev_substance_1_5","stem":"Your AUD patient has significant hepatic impairment / alcoholic liver disease. Which agent is the safest choice because it is renally excreted unchanged rather than hepatically metabolized or overtly hepatotoxic?","options":["Acamprosate","Disulfiram","Naltrexone","Varenicline"],"answer":"Acamprosate","explanation":"Acamprosate bypasses hepatic metabolism (renally excreted unchanged), so it is a good fit in alcoholic liver disease — provided renal function is adequate. Disulfiram can cause fulminant hepatotoxicity and naltrexone is dose-dependently hepatotoxic, both less ideal here; varenicline targets nicotine, not alcohol.","meds":["acamprosate","disulfiram","naltrexone","varenicline"],"focus":"organ-based selection: liver-sparing acamprosate vs hepatotoxic disulfiram/naltrexone","source":{"name":"Acamprosate product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"acamprosate"}],"substance:2":[{"id":"rev_substance_2_1","stem":"You want the PARTIAL mu-opioid agonist whose ceiling on respiratory depression makes it safer in overdose than methadone and whose QT effect is minimal by comparison. Which single agent fits?","options":["Buprenorphine","Methadone","Naltrexone","Naloxone"],"answer":"Buprenorphine","explanation":"Buprenorphine is a high-affinity partial mu agonist (with kappa antagonism): the partial activation gives a ceiling on respiratory depression, so it is safer in overdose than full-agonist methadone, and its QT effect is much smaller. Methadone is the full agonist with dose-dependent QT/torsades; naltrexone and naloxone are antagonists.","meds":["buprenorphine","methadone","naltrexone","naloxone"],"focus":"partial-agonist ceiling / minimal QT (buprenorphine) vs full-agonist methadone","source":{"name":"Buprenorphine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"buprenorphine"},{"id":"rev_substance_2_2","stem":"Because this agent's high mu affinity DISPLACES full agonists, starting it too soon precipitates withdrawal — so you wait for objective withdrawal (COWS) or use a micro-dosing induction. Which agent requires that timing?","options":["Buprenorphine","Methadone","Naltrexone","Naloxone"],"answer":"Buprenorphine","explanation":"Buprenorphine's high receptor affinity plus low intrinsic activity means it knocks full agonists off the receptor, precipitating withdrawal if given before the patient is in objective withdrawal — hence wait for COWS or micro-dose. Methadone (full agonist) is started low/slow without that displacement issue; naltrexone precipitates withdrawal by full antagonism and needs a 7-10 day washout, not COWS timing; naloxone is emergency reversal.","meds":["buprenorphine","methadone","naltrexone","naloxone"],"focus":"buprenorphine induction timing / precipitated withdrawal (COWS, micro-dosing)","source":{"name":"Buprenorphine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"buprenorphine"},{"id":"rev_substance_2_3","stem":"Compared with the sublingual buprenorphine/naloxone COMBINATION, which product is the plain partial agonist that LACKS the added naloxone abuse-deterrent component (as used in mono formulations)?","options":["Buprenorphine","Buprenorphine/naloxone","Methadone","Naltrexone"],"answer":"Buprenorphine","explanation":"Mono buprenorphine is the partial agonist WITHOUT naloxone; the combination adds naloxone (inert sublingually, but precipitates withdrawal if injected) purely as an abuse-deterrent. The pharmacology at the mu receptor is the same buprenorphine — the difference is the missing deterrent. Methadone is a full agonist and naltrexone an antagonist.","meds":["buprenorphine","buprenorphine_naloxone","methadone","naltrexone"],"focus":"buprenorphine mono vs combo — absence of the naloxone abuse-deterrent","source":{"name":"Buprenorphine product monograph","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"buprenorphine"}],"dementia:0":[{"id":"rev_dementia_0_1","stem":"You are starting a cholinesterase inhibitor for a patient whose caregiver worries about occasionally forgetting a dose. Which agent has the longest half-life, allowing simple once-daily dosing that is the most forgiving of an occasional missed dose?","options":["Donepezil","Rivastigmine","Galantamine","Memantine"],"answer":"Donepezil","explanation":"Donepezil has the longest half-life of the cholinesterase inhibitors, so it is given once daily and tolerates an occasional missed dose. Rivastigmine is the contrast here: short-acting, and after an interruption of more than about 3 days it must be restarted low and re-titrated because resuming the prior dose risks severe vomiting. Galantamine is also shorter-acting (IR is twice daily), and memantine is not a cholinesterase inhibitor at all.","meds":["donepezil","rivastigmine","galantamine","memantine"],"focus":"Donepezil = longest half-life, once daily, forgiving of a missed dose","source":{"name":"Donepezil / rivastigmine monographs — half-life and dosing","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"donepezil"},{"id":"rev_dementia_0_2","stem":"A patient on an oral cholinesterase inhibitor has recurrent nausea and vomiting and adherence to twice-daily capsules is poor. You want an agent available as a transdermal patch that smooths drug levels to reduce GI side effects and improve adherence. Which one do you choose?","options":["Rivastigmine","Donepezil","Galantamine","Memantine"],"answer":"Rivastigmine","explanation":"Rivastigmine is the cholinesterase inhibitor available as a transdermal patch; smoother plasma levels from the patch cut GI side effects and improve adherence versus oral dosing. Donepezil and galantamine come only as oral formulations (tablet/ODT and tablet/ER capsule respectively), and memantine is an oral NMDA antagonist, not a cholinesterase inhibitor.","meds":["rivastigmine","donepezil","galantamine","memantine"],"focus":"Rivastigmine = transdermal patch reduces GI side effects and aids adherence","source":{"name":"Rivastigmine monograph — transdermal patch formulation","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"rivastigmine"},{"id":"rev_dementia_0_3","stem":"Which cholinesterase inhibitor is distinguished by inhibiting BOTH acetylcholinesterase and butyrylcholinesterase, is metabolised by esterases rather than CYP enzymes (few CYP interactions), and is the only one in the class also approved for Parkinson disease dementia?","options":["Rivastigmine","Donepezil","Galantamine","Memantine"],"answer":"Rivastigmine","explanation":"Rivastigmine is a pseudo-irreversible carbamate that inhibits both acetylcholinesterase and butyrylcholinesterase, is cleared by esterases (not CYP, so few CYP drug interactions), and is the only cholinesterase inhibitor also approved for Parkinson disease dementia. Donepezil is a centrally selective AChE-only inhibitor; galantamine adds nicotinic modulation but does not inhibit butyrylcholinesterase; memantine is an NMDA antagonist.","meds":["rivastigmine","donepezil","galantamine","memantine"],"focus":"Rivastigmine = dual AChE + BuChE, esterase metabolism, Parkinson disease dementia","source":{"name":"Rivastigmine monograph — dual esterase inhibition and indications","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"rivastigmine"},{"id":"rev_dementia_0_4","stem":"A patient started on a bedtime cholinesterase inhibitor now reports vivid, disturbing dreams and nightmares, and moving the dose to the morning is expected to help. Which agent is this pattern most characteristic of?","options":["Donepezil","Rivastigmine","Galantamine","Memantine"],"answer":"Donepezil","explanation":"Donepezil taken at bedtime is classically associated with vivid dreams/nightmares and insomnia; because its long half-life allows flexible once-daily timing, simply moving the dose to the morning usually resolves this. Rivastigmine and galantamine are dosed with food and are less identified with this bedtime nightmare pattern, and memantine (an NMDA antagonist) causes dizziness/constipation/confusion rather than the cholinergic-sleep effects.","meds":["donepezil","rivastigmine","galantamine","memantine"],"focus":"Donepezil = bedtime vivid dreams/nightmares; move dose to the morning","source":{"name":"Donepezil monograph — sleep/dosing-time adverse effects","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"donepezil"}],"dementia:1":[{"id":"rev_dementia_1_1","stem":"A patient with moderate-to-severe Alzheimer disease is already on a well-tolerated cholinesterase inhibitor but is declining. You want to ADD an agent with a completely different mechanism that can be safely combined with the cholinesterase inhibitor. Which do you add?","options":["Memantine","Galantamine","Donepezil","Rivastigmine"],"answer":"Memantine","explanation":"Memantine is an uncompetitive NMDA-receptor antagonist — a mechanism entirely distinct from the cholinesterase inhibitors — so it can be combined with a cholinesterase inhibitor in moderate-to-severe Alzheimer disease. Adding a second cholinesterase inhibitor (galantamine, donepezil, or rivastigmine) instead would not add a new mechanism and would compound cholinergic GI and bradycardic toxicity.","meds":["memantine","galantamine","donepezil","rivastigmine"],"focus":"Memantine = distinct NMDA mechanism, combinable with a ChEI in moderate-severe disease","source":{"name":"Memantine monograph — NMDA antagonism and combination therapy","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"memantine"},{"id":"rev_dementia_1_2","stem":"Which add-on dementia agent works through a DUAL cholinergic mechanism — reversible acetylcholinesterase inhibition PLUS allosteric potentiation of nicotinic acetylcholine receptors — and is approved only for mild-to-moderate Alzheimer disease?","options":["Galantamine","Memantine","Donepezil","Rivastigmine"],"answer":"Galantamine","explanation":"Galantamine combines competitive, reversible acetylcholinesterase inhibition with allosteric potentiation of nicotinic receptors, and is indicated for mild-to-moderate Alzheimer disease only. Memantine is an NMDA antagonist (no cholinergic action) reserved for moderate-severe disease; donepezil is a centrally selective AChE-only inhibitor; rivastigmine's second target is butyrylcholinesterase, not nicotinic modulation.","meds":["galantamine","memantine","donepezil","rivastigmine"],"focus":"Galantamine = AChE inhibition PLUS nicotinic allosteric potentiation, mild-moderate only","source":{"name":"Galantamine monograph — dual cholinergic mechanism and indication","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"galantamine"},{"id":"rev_dementia_1_3","stem":"You need a dementia agent for a patient with significant renal impairment and a low tolerance for cholinergic GI upset and bradycardia. Which agent is renally excreted largely unchanged (requiring dose reduction in severe renal impairment) and lacks the cholinergic GI and bradycardic effects of the other agents?","options":["Memantine","Galantamine","Donepezil","Rivastigmine"],"answer":"Memantine","explanation":"Memantine is excreted renally, largely unchanged, so it must be dose-reduced in severe renal impairment — contrasting the hepatically-metabolised cholinesterase inhibitors. As an NMDA antagonist it produces no cholinergic GI upset or bradycardia; its main issues are dizziness, constipation, and confusion. Galantamine, donepezil, and rivastigmine all carry the class cholinergic nausea/vomiting and bradycardia/syncope risk.","meds":["memantine","galantamine","donepezil","rivastigmine"],"focus":"Memantine = renally cleared (dose-reduce in renal impairment), no cholinergic GI/bradycardia","source":{"name":"Memantine monograph — renal excretion and tolerability","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"memantine"},{"id":"rev_dementia_1_4","stem":"Two add-on agents remain. One is a cholinesterase inhibitor that should be taken with food and fluids to limit nausea, is restricted to mild-to-moderate Alzheimer disease, and carries an excess-mortality signal from trials in mild cognitive impairment (not an approved use). Which agent is this?","options":["Galantamine","Memantine","Donepezil","Rivastigmine"],"answer":"Galantamine","explanation":"Galantamine is approved for mild-to-moderate Alzheimer only, is taken with food and fluids to reduce cholinergic nausea, and showed an excess-mortality signal in mild-cognitive-impairment trials — a non-approved indication. Memantine (the other add-on) is an NMDA antagonist reserved for moderate-severe disease, without that cholinergic tolerability profile; donepezil and rivastigmine are the tier-0 cholinesterase inhibitors, not the mild-cognitive-impairment mortality signal drug.","meds":["galantamine","memantine","donepezil","rivastigmine"],"focus":"Galantamine = mild-moderate only, take with food, MCI excess-mortality signal","source":{"name":"Galantamine monograph — indication limits and mild-cognitive-impairment safety signal","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"galantamine"}],"adjunct:0":[{"id":"rev_adjunct_0_1","stem":"Two hours after his first dose of intramuscular haloperidol, a young man develops a painful, sustained upward and lateral eye deviation with neck twisting (oculogyric crisis). Which agent, given IM, reverses this fastest?","options":["Propranolol","Amantadine","Benztropine"],"answer":"Benztropine","explanation":"This is an acute dystonic reaction — D2 blockade acutely unbalances striatal acetylcholine against dopamine, and an IM/IV central anticholinergic (benztropine) rebalances it within minutes, so it is the rescue agent. Propranolol, the other tier-0 adjunct, is first-line for AKATHISIA, not dystonia, and would do nothing here. Amantadine is a dopaminergic/NMDA agent for drug-induced parkinsonism that works orally and slowly — not an acute-dystonia rescue.","meds":["propranolol","amantadine","benztropine"],"focus":"acute dystonia/EPS -> anticholinergic (IM benztropine); propranolol is for akathisia, not dystonia","source":{"name":"Benztropine product monograph - acute dystonia / drug-induced EPS","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"benztropine"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_0_2","stem":"Two weeks into risperidone, a woman paces relentlessly and describes an unbearable inner restlessness she rates as worse than her psychosis. A trial of an oral anticholinergic gave no relief. She has no asthma, bradycardia, or heart block. Which is first-line?","options":["Propranolol","Benztropine"],"answer":"Propranolol","explanation":"Her restlessness is antipsychotic-induced akathisia, for which the non-selective beta-blocker propranolol is first-line; the failed anticholinergic trial is the classic clue, because anticholinergics do not reliably relieve akathisia. Benztropine treats acute dystonia and drug-induced parkinsonism by rebalancing striatal ACh:dopamine, but it does not fix the noradrenergically driven restlessness of akathisia. (Confirm no asthma/bradycardia/AV block before starting propranolol.)","meds":["propranolol","benztropine"],"focus":"akathisia -> propranolol; anticholinergics (benztropine) do not reliably help akathisia","source":{"name":"CANMAT / movement-disorder guidance - antipsychotic-induced akathisia","origin":"canmat"},"answerId":"propranolol"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_0_3","stem":"On a high-potency antipsychotic, a patient develops a resting tremor, cogwheel rigidity, and bradykinesia (drug-induced parkinsonism). Which of these two adjuncts rebalances striatal acetylcholine against dopamine to relieve it?","options":["Benztropine","Propranolol"],"answer":"Benztropine","explanation":"Benztropine's central anticholinergic action restores the striatal dopamine:acetylcholine balance disrupted by D2 blockade, so it relieves BOTH acute dystonia and drug-induced parkinsonism. Propranolol, a beta-blocker, targets akathisia and tremor via adrenergic blockade but does nothing for parkinsonian rigidity/bradykinesia. Trade-off to remember: benztropine adds anticholinergic burden (dry mouth, constipation, urinary retention, confusion in the elderly) and can WORSEN tardive dyskinesia.","meds":["benztropine","propranolol"],"focus":"key difference - anticholinergic (benztropine) covers dystonia + parkinsonism; beta-blocker (propranolol) covers akathisia","source":{"name":"Benztropine product monograph - drug-induced parkinsonism","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"benztropine"}],"adjunct:1":[{"id":"rev_adjunct_1_1","stem":"A veteran with PTSD has recurrent trauma nightmares and fragmented sleep. Which adjunct, dosed at bedtime and titrated up, is the off-label go-to?","options":["Amantadine","Prazosin","Procyclidine","Trihexyphenidyl"],"answer":"Prazosin","explanation":"Prazosin is a selective alpha-1 antagonist that blunts the central noradrenergic surge implicated in trauma nightmares; it is the off-label go-to for PTSD nightmares and trauma-related sleep disruption. Procyclidine and trihexyphenidyl are anticholinergics for EPS, and amantadine is a dopaminergic/NMDA agent for drug-induced parkinsonism — none target trauma nightmares. Warn about the first-dose orthostatic drop: start 1 mg at bedtime.","meds":["amantadine","prazosin","procyclidine","trihexyphenidyl"],"focus":"PTSD nightmares -> alpha-1 antagonist (prazosin), not the anticholinergic/dopaminergic EPS agents","source":{"name":"Prazosin product monograph - PTSD-nightmare use","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"prazosin"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_1_2","stem":"You must treat drug-induced parkinsonism in an elderly man already burdened by constipation and urinary retention, so you want to AVOID adding anticholinergic load. Which agent — a dopaminergic/NMDA drug whose signature adverse effects are livedo reticularis and ankle edema — fits?","options":["Procyclidine","Trihexyphenidyl","Amantadine","Prazosin"],"answer":"Amantadine","explanation":"Amantadine enhances dopamine release and antagonizes NMDA receptors, treating drug-induced parkinsonism with far LESS anticholinergic burden than benztropine/procyclidine/trihexyphenidyl — ideal when anticholinergic effects are already a problem. Its signature adverse effects are livedo reticularis and ankle edema; it is renally excreted unchanged (reduce dose in renal impairment) and must not be stopped abruptly. Procyclidine and trihexyphenidyl would ADD anticholinergic burden; prazosin is an alpha-1 blocker for PTSD nightmares.","meds":["procyclidine","trihexyphenidyl","amantadine","prazosin"],"focus":"drug-induced parkinsonism with low anticholinergic burden -> amantadine (livedo reticularis, ankle edema)","source":{"name":"Amantadine product monograph - drug-induced parkinsonism / adverse effects","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"amantadine"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_1_3","stem":"Among the anticholinergic EPS agents, one is notable for a euphoriant/hallucinogenic misuse potential and is sometimes diverted. Which one warrants extra vigilance for diversion (and is also contraindicated in narrow-angle glaucoma)?","options":["Trihexyphenidyl","Procyclidine","Amantadine","Prazosin"],"answer":"Trihexyphenidyl","explanation":"Trihexyphenidyl, though a standard anticholinergic for EPS/parkinsonism, carries a distinctive euphoriant/hallucinogenic misuse liability (unlike its peers) — watch for diversion; it is also contraindicated in narrow-angle glaucoma. Procyclidine is an essentially interchangeable anticholinergic WITHOUT that misuse profile. Amantadine (dopaminergic/NMDA) and prazosin (alpha-1 blocker) are not anticholinergics at all.","meds":["trihexyphenidyl","procyclidine","amantadine","prazosin"],"focus":"key difference - trihexyphenidyl's euphoriant misuse/diversion potential among the anticholinergics","source":{"name":"Trihexyphenidyl product monograph - misuse potential / glaucoma","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"trihexyphenidyl"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_1_4","stem":"You want a short-acting anticholinergic (typically dosed three times daily) that is essentially interchangeable with benztropine for acute dystonia and drug-induced parkinsonism, but WITHOUT the euphoriant misuse liability of trihexyphenidyl. Which agent?","options":["Trihexyphenidyl","Amantadine","Procyclidine","Prazosin"],"answer":"Procyclidine","explanation":"Procyclidine is a central anticholinergic essentially interchangeable with benztropine for drug-induced EPS, more often dosed TID (shorter-acting), and it lacks the euphoriant/diversion liability that distinguishes trihexyphenidyl. Like all anticholinergics it helps acute dystonia and parkinsonism but NOT akathisia, and can worsen tardive dyskinesia. Amantadine is dopaminergic (not anticholinergic); prazosin is an alpha-1 blocker.","meds":["trihexyphenidyl","amantadine","procyclidine","prazosin"],"focus":"procyclidine - TID anticholinergic interchangeable with benztropine, no euphoriant misuse (vs trihexyphenidyl)","source":{"name":"Procyclidine product monograph - drug-induced EPS","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"procyclidine"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_1_5","stem":"You start one of these adjuncts and specifically warn the patient to take the FIRST dose at bedtime because of a risk of marked orthostatic hypotension and syncope on initiation. Which agent's 'first-dose phenomenon' is this?","options":["Amantadine","Procyclidine","Trihexyphenidyl","Prazosin"],"answer":"Prazosin","explanation":"Prazosin's alpha-1 blockade produces a well-described first-dose phenomenon — marked orthostatic hypotension/syncope — so it is started at 1 mg at bedtime and titrated up. The anticholinergics (procyclidine, trihexyphenidyl) can cause dizziness but not this vasodilatory first-dose collapse, and amantadine causes ankle edema/livedo rather than orthostatic first-dose syncope. This initiation caveat is what sets prazosin apart in the row.","meds":["amantadine","procyclidine","trihexyphenidyl","prazosin"],"focus":"key difference - prazosin's first-dose orthostatic hypotension (bedtime start), unique to the alpha-1 blocker","source":{"name":"Prazosin product monograph - first-dose phenomenon","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"prazosin"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_1_6","stem":"The other adjuncts in this row block muscarinic (procyclidine, trihexyphenidyl) or alpha-1 (prazosin) receptors. Which agent instead ENHANCES dopamine and blocks NMDA — a mechanism that makes it a useful tardive-dyskinesia adjunct, and that requires renal dose reduction and no abrupt discontinuation?","options":["Procyclidine","Prazosin","Trihexyphenidyl","Amantadine"],"answer":"Amantadine","explanation":"Amantadine is the row's dopaminergic/NMDA-antagonist — unlike the anticholinergics or prazosin's alpha-1 blockade — which underlies its use for drug-induced parkinsonism and as a tardive-dyskinesia adjunct. Because it is renally excreted unchanged, the dose must be reduced in renal impairment, and abrupt discontinuation can precipitate an NMS-like withdrawal. Critically, the anticholinergics WORSEN tardive dyskinesia, so amantadine's dopaminergic mechanism is the safer adjunct when TD coexists.","meds":["procyclidine","prazosin","trihexyphenidyl","amantadine"],"focus":"key difference - amantadine is dopaminergic/NMDA (not anticholinergic/alpha-1); renal dosing, TD-adjunct, no abrupt stop","source":{"name":"Amantadine product monograph - mechanism, renal excretion, discontinuation","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"amantadine"}],"adjunct:2":[{"id":"rev_adjunct_2_1","stem":"You want to start a VMAT2 inhibitor for tardive dyskinesia in a Canadian patient, using an agent actually marketed in Canada (brand Nitoman). Which one?","options":["Valbenazine","Deutetrabenazine","Tetrabenazine","Modafinil"],"answer":"Tetrabenazine","explanation":"Tetrabenazine (Nitoman) is the VMAT2 inhibitor available in Canada, labelled for hyperkinetic movement disorders including Huntington chorea and tardive dyskinesia. Valbenazine (Ingrezza) and deutetrabenazine (Austedo) are VMAT2 inhibitors approved in the US but NOT marketed in Canada. Modafinil is a wakefulness-promoting agent, unrelated to TD.","meds":["valbenazine","deutetrabenazine","tetrabenazine","modafinil"],"focus":"Canadian availability - tetrabenazine (Nitoman) is the VMAT2 inhibitor sold in Canada; valbenazine/deutetrabenazine are US-only","source":{"name":"Tetrabenazine (Nitoman) product monograph - hyperkinetic movement disorders","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"tetrabenazine"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_2_2","stem":"Among the VMAT2 inhibitors for tardive dyskinesia, which US-only agent (Ingrezza) is a purified/prodrug relative of tetrabenazine offering ONCE-DAILY dosing and generally better tolerability?","options":["Tetrabenazine","Valbenazine","Deutetrabenazine","Dexmedetomidine"],"answer":"Valbenazine","explanation":"Valbenazine is a purified/prodrug relative of tetrabenazine given once daily with generally better tolerability — its key advantage over tetrabenazine. It is a US drug (Ingrezza) not marketed in Canada. Deutetrabenazine is dosed twice daily, and tetrabenazine (the Canadian Nitoman) has the shortest-acting, least-tolerable profile of the three. Dexmedetomidine is an alpha-2 agonist for agitation, not a VMAT2 inhibitor.","meds":["tetrabenazine","valbenazine","deutetrabenazine","dexmedetomidine"],"focus":"valbenazine - once-daily VMAT2 inhibitor, better tolerability than tetrabenazine (US-only)","source":{"name":"Valbenazine (Ingrezza) product monograph - once-daily VMAT2 inhibitor","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"valbenazine"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_2_3","stem":"Which VMAT2 inhibitor is the DEUTERATED form of tetrabenazine — carbon-deuterium bonds slowing metabolism of the active metabolites to give steadier levels and twice-daily dosing (US brand Austedo, approved for both tardive dyskinesia and Huntington chorea)?","options":["Valbenazine","Tetrabenazine","Deutetrabenazine","Armodafinil"],"answer":"Deutetrabenazine","explanation":"Deutetrabenazine is tetrabenazine with deuterium substituted at key positions; the stronger carbon-deuterium bonds slow metabolism of the active HTBZ metabolites, smoothing levels and allowing BID dosing with better tolerability than tetrabenazine. It is US-only (Austedo), approved for both TD and Huntington chorea. Valbenazine is a once-daily prodrug relative; tetrabenazine is the parent (Canadian Nitoman); armodafinil is a wakefulness agent.","meds":["valbenazine","tetrabenazine","deutetrabenazine","armodafinil"],"focus":"deutetrabenazine - deuterated tetrabenazine -> smoother levels, BID dosing (US-only)","source":{"name":"Deutetrabenazine (Austedo) product monograph - deuteration, BID dosing","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"deutetrabenazine"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_2_4","stem":"A woman with narcolepsy needs a wakefulness-promoting agent that IS marketed in Canada. Which agent — a CYP3A4 inducer that lowers oral-contraceptive efficacy, so you counsel backup contraception — fits?","options":["Modafinil","Armodafinil","Dexmedetomidine","Valbenazine"],"answer":"Modafinil","explanation":"Modafinil is a wakefulness-promoting agent approved in Canada for narcolepsy, obstructive sleep apnea (adjunct to CPAP), and shift-work disorder; as a CYP3A4 INDUCER it lowers oral-contraceptive efficacy, so counsel backup contraception during use and for about one month after. Armodafinil is its R-enantiomer with the same caveat but is US-only (Nuvigil). Dexmedetomidine (alpha-2 agonist) and valbenazine (VMAT2) treat agitation and TD, not sleepiness.","meds":["modafinil","armodafinil","dexmedetomidine","valbenazine"],"focus":"excessive sleepiness/narcolepsy -> modafinil (Canada); CYP3A4 inducer lowers oral-contraceptive efficacy","source":{"name":"Modafinil product monograph - narcolepsy, CYP3A4 induction / contraception","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"modafinil"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_2_5","stem":"Which wakefulness-promoting agent is simply the longer-acting R-(minus)-enantiomer of modafinil — sustaining wakefulness later into the day, and marketed in the US as Nuvigil (not available in Canada)?","options":["Modafinil","Armodafinil","Tetrabenazine","Dexmedetomidine"],"answer":"Armodafinil","explanation":"Armodafinil is the single R-enantiomer of racemic modafinil; being longer-acting it sustains wakefulness further into the day, but it is US-only (Nuvigil) whereas MODAFINIL is the version available in Canada. It shares modafinil's CYP3A4-induction/contraceptive caveat and Schedule-IV misuse potential. Tetrabenazine (VMAT2 inhibitor) and dexmedetomidine (alpha-2 agonist) are unrelated in mechanism and indication.","meds":["modafinil","armodafinil","tetrabenazine","dexmedetomidine"],"focus":"key difference - armodafinil is the longer-acting R-enantiomer of modafinil (US-only vs modafinil in Canada)","source":{"name":"Armodafinil (Nuvigil) product monograph - R-enantiomer of modafinil","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"armodafinil"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_2_6","stem":"A patient with schizophrenia is acutely agitated. Which specialist adjunct is a sublingual alpha-2-adrenergic agonist FILM that calms agitation WITHOUT the EPS risk of antipsychotics — but requires blood-pressure and heart-rate monitoring for hypotension and bradycardia?","options":["Modafinil","Deutetrabenazine","Tetrabenazine","Dexmedetomidine"],"answer":"Dexmedetomidine","explanation":"Dexmedetomidine is a selective alpha-2 agonist; its sublingual/buccal film (US Igalmi) treats acute agitation in schizophrenia or bipolar I/II by reducing central sympathetic outflow — calming without dopamine blockade, so no EPS, but with hypotension/bradycardia/orthostasis requiring cardiovascular monitoring. Modafinil PROMOTES wakefulness (the opposite of sedation); deutetrabenazine and tetrabenazine are VMAT2 inhibitors for hyperkinetic movements, not agitation.","meds":["modafinil","deutetrabenazine","tetrabenazine","dexmedetomidine"],"focus":"acute agitation -> alpha-2 agonist (dexmedetomidine); calms without EPS, needs BP/HR monitoring","source":{"name":"Dexmedetomidine sublingual (Igalmi) product monograph - acute agitation","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"dexmedetomidine"},{"id":"rev_adjunct_2_7","stem":"VMAT2 inhibitors treat tardive dyskinesia by DEPLETING dopamine — the mechanistic opposite of what drives drug-induced parkinsonism. Which of these agents can therefore itself CAUSE depression/suicidality and parkinsonism, mandating a mood screen and avoidance in active depression?","options":["Modafinil","Armodafinil","Dexmedetomidine","Tetrabenazine"],"answer":"Tetrabenazine","explanation":"Tetrabenazine depletes presynaptic dopamine (and serotonin/norepinephrine) via VMAT2 inhibition; because that depletion can precipitate depression/suicidality and drug-induced parkinsonism, its label warns against use in active or inadequately treated depression and requires mood monitoring. (Its VMAT2 relatives valbenazine and deutetrabenazine share this class caveat, but tetrabenazine is the only dopamine-depleter among these options.) Modafinil and armodafinil RAISE dopaminergic tone for wakefulness, and dexmedetomidine is an alpha-2 agonist — none deplete dopamine.","meds":["modafinil","armodafinil","dexmedetomidine","tetrabenazine"],"focus":"key difference - VMAT2 dopamine depletion (tetrabenazine) causes depression/parkinsonism; screen mood, avoid in active depression","source":{"name":"Tetrabenazine (Nitoman) product monograph - depression/parkinsonism from dopamine depletion","origin":"monograph"},"answerId":"tetrabenazine"}]};
